surveys.narrative:
This sub survey contains data from 8 mid-lake gill net sets that were first set in 1997. These nets were initially set to determine if catch rate and growth statistics for various fish species were similar to those of the 24 near-shore gill net sets.

Data from this survey should not be used to independently evaluate Lake Winnibigoshish fish populations, or to compare between years within lake or between different lakes as the data are from a subset of nets contributing to a larger study.

The walleye population appeared to be healthy with ten age classes sampled between age 1 and age 12. Year class strength was computed for walleye between age 2 and age 7. Two weak year classes, three average year classes, and the strong 2001 year class were present. The 1994 and 1995 year classes exceeded age seven, were relatively abundant, and contributed to the above average catch of 18 to 23 inch walleye. Mean back-calculated growth was fast for most age classes, attaining 16.5 inches after four growing seasons.

Yellow perch were sampled at a rate of 54.7 per near-shore gill net. This was the lowest catch rate observed since 1983, and was lower than typical for Lake Winnibigoshish. Perch sampled in near-shore gill nets varied from 4.9 to 11.8 inches with a mean length of 7.9 inches.

Yellow perch growth was slow for age 1 and age 2, and average from age 3 through age 10. Near shore and mid-lake gill net catch rates were similar between 1997 and 2002. However, the mid-lake gill net catch rate was nearly double the near-shore gill net catch rate in 2003. From 1997 to 2000 the percent of perch larger than 9 inches was similar between near-shore and mid-lake gill nets. Since 2000 the percent of perch larger than 9 inches has been divergent, with a higher percentage larger than 9 inches sampled in mid-lake sets.

All age classes between age-2 and age-10 were sampled by gill net. Year class strength was computed for yellow perch between age 3 and age 7. Of these, the 1996 (age 4) through 1999 (age 7) year classes were average and the 2000 year class was considered weak. The catch of age-8, 9, and 10 perch was much lower than that of ages 3 through 7, and was a relatively small component of the total catch. Relative health of the yellow perch population has been described by the percent of perch larger than 9 inches in the gill net catch. Twenty six percent of the near-shore gill net sampled perch were larger than 9 inches. Yellow perch growth was relatively slow through age 2, and increased to near average from age 3 to age 10, attaining a mean length of 9.4 inches at age 6.

Northern pike were sampled at a rate of 8.3 per near-shore gill net which was typical compared to similiar lakes and for Lake Winnibigoshish. Pike sampled in near-shore gill nets varied from 6.7 to 34.3 inches with a mean length of 22.0 inches.

All age classes between age-1 and age-7 were sampled by gill net. Age 2, 3, 4,and 5 pike were similarly represented in the gill net catch. Northern pike sampled in near shore-gill nets reached a mean length of 24.7 inches at age 5. Stomach contents were evaluated for all pike sampled in 2003. Of 189 pike sampled, 32 had recognizable prey in their stomachs. The most frequent prey item observed was yellow perch, however, most perch were consumed by pike less than 22 inches in length. Cisco were the most frequent prey item of pike 22 inches and longer.

The gill net catch rates of cisco remained low in 2003. The catch rate of 18.0 per near-shore net followed the trend of reduced catch rates since 1997. Bony structures were not collected from cisco in 2003 and ages were not determined. Examination of the cisco length frequency indicates that recruitment was sporadic and year classes may be absent.

Assessment of Lake Winnibigoshish is completed annually to track changes in abundance and growth of fish species, and physical and chemical characteristics of the lake. The assessment season typically starts with seining and gill netting in late June to early July. The goal of seining is to sample young game and non-game species (including minnows) and to track growth of age-0 walleye and yellow perch (perch). Gill netting is conducted from late June through July to sample game and non-game species age 1 and older. Abundance, growth rates, maturity, presence of parasites etc. is determined from these data. Trawling is conducted in August to continue tracking growth rates of age-0 walleye and perch. Trawling gives us the first clue to abundance of age-0 walleye and perch for that year. Temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles are taken from June through August and water chemistry analysis is done in August to track changes in the system that may affect the ability of some species to prosper or exist in the lake. Plankton sampling was included in standard sampling for 2012. Five samples were taken on eight dates for a total of 40 samples. These samples were taken to determine baseline planktonic species composition.

Walleye; Walleye were sampled at a historic high rate of 9.6 per net. Walleye sampled varied from 8.3 to 26.7 inches with a mean length of 16.3 inches and mean weight of 1.4 pounds. The walleye population appeared to be healthy with most age classes sampled between age 1 and 16. Year-class strength was computed for walleye between age 2 and 7. Two average year classes (2005, and 2007), three strong year classes (2006 and 2009, and 2010), and one weak year class (2008) were sampled. Mean back calculated growth was similar to the Lake Winnibigoshish and statewide average for all ages, attaining 16.7 inches after five growing seasons.

The mean trawl catch rate of 35.6 walleye per hour was lower than average, however, low catch rates may not result in low abundance of that year class. For example, the trawl catch rate of 20.5 young of the year walleye per hour in 2005 resulted in an above average year class. An important factor in year-class strength is growth of those fish during their first year. Young of the year walleye growth was above average in 2012, reaching a mean length of 5.0 inches by mid-August. Fast growth of age 0 walleye often results in a strong year class.

Yellow perch; Perch are an important species both for anglers and as a prey item for predators. The catch of perch in assessment nets reached a historic low catch rate (at the time) in 2005 largely due to poor year classes in 2000 and 2002. A strong 2003 year class moved through the system resulting in higher assessment catch rates through 2007. Gill net catch rates then declined through 2011 to a new historic low of 43.6 per net that year.

Perch were captured at a rate of 57.5 per net in 2012. Perch sampled varied from 5.0 to 11.5 inches with a mean length of 7.1 inches and mean weight of 0.2 pounds. Age classes 2 through 8 and were sampled by the gill nets. An index of year class strength was computed for ages 3 through 7. The 2005, 2008 and 2009 year classes were average, and the 2006 and 2007 year classes were weak. The previously strong 2003 and average 2004 year classes were not well represented in the catch. Natural mortality of perch increases at age 9 and few individuals live past age 10. The catch of perch in 2012 was primarily represented by younger individuals with 87% of the catch made up of age 3 through age 5 fish. Growth was relatively slow through age 2, then increased to average from age 3 to age 8. Perch grew to an average length of 9 inches at age 6.

Relative health of the perch population can be described by the percent of perch longer than nine inches in the gill net catch. The catch of large perch declined to 6% in the early 1990's driven by high angler harvest. Changes in the perch population of Lake Winnibigoshish and other lakes prompted a statewide change in the perch bag limit to 20 daily and 40 in possession in 2001. Several strong year classes were produced during the same time period and the assessment catch of perch longer than nine inches increased to 30% in 2004. In 2005, the proportion of large perch sampled in near-shore gill nets declined for the first time since 1998. The proportion of perch longer than nine inches was about 17% in 2005 and 2006, then declined to 9.8% in 2007 as young perch were recruited to the fishery. Many small fish remain in the population and 10% of the perch sampled in 2012 were longer than nine inches.

The microsporidian parasite heterosporis has been documented in Lake Winnibigoshish yellow perch. No evidence of heterosporis was observed in perch during the 2012 population assessment, however, anglers report the presence of heterosporis in a few perch each year.

The catch rate for age-0 perch of 10,720 per hour of trawling was average. Growth of age-0 perch was slower than average with a mean length of 1.7 inches in mid August. No correlation is evident between trawl catch rates or growth of age-0 perch and year-class strength.

Northern pike; Catch rates of northern pike (pike) showed an increasing trend from 1999 through 2005 and exceeded the third quartile (9.6 per net) in five years between 2002 and 2009. The pike catch rate decreased to 7.3 per gill net in 2010 from 10.0 in 2009 then rose to 8.5 in 2011 and was the third highest observed in 2012 at 10.3 per net. Pike sampled in 2012 varied from 13.9 to 34.1 inches with a mean length of 21.6 inches. All age classes from 1 to 8 were sampled by gill net. The 2009 and 2010 year classes were most abundant and contributed 64% of the catch. Growth rates were similar to the statewide mean through all ages.

Size structure of the pike population has been improving for the last three years. That trend continued in 2012 and extended to the largest fish in the system. Mean length and the number of pike longer than 30 inches was similar to those from 2011 and higher than in any assessments since 2000. Increased size structure can be attributed to several causes. Cisco abundance has increased (cisco are preferred prey that provides more energy than other similar size prey), which may lead to faster growth rates. Reduced abundance of pike may also be beneficial to the pike population since increased pike density can cause more competition for food and space which may lead to decrease growth. The recent increase in catch rate may resut in slower pike growth in the future. Anglers can help maintain the pike size structure by releasing most pike longer than 25 inches.


Cisco; Cisco are a primary prey for muskellunge, pike and walleye. Growth rates of these species can be reduced if cisco are not present in the system. The gill net catch of 16.0 cisco per net in 2012 was nearly identical to the catch of 16.4 per net in 2011. Cisco sampled varied from 6.9 to 16.4 inches with a mean length of 11.3 inches. Cisco catch rates were lower than average for 5 of the last 10 years. This is likely due to warmer than average summer and fall water temperatures that may affect reproduction and cause occasional summer kills. Summer water temperatures were warm during the summer of 2012. This resulted in a moderate summer kill of cisco. Any effect on the cisco population should be short term if average temperatures are experienced in the near future.

Water Quality; Seven temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken between June 25 and August 20, 2012. Dissolved oxygen stratification was evident between July 2 and July 27. No evidence of thermal stratification was found in 2012. Thermal and dissolved oxygen stratification may result during periods of high air temperatures and low wind. When wind speeds increase to moderate levels (15 mph) the entire water column appears to mix.

Invasive Aquatic Species; Species that have been introduced through human activities to a location where they don't naturally occur are termed "invasive". Some invasive species are not necessarily harmful, but others cause ecological or economic problems. Several invasive species have been introduced to Lake Winnibigoshish. Three species of snail: banded mystery, Chinese mystery, and faucet have become established since 2000. Both species of mystery snail appear to have no negative effect at this time. The faucet snail carries a trematode parasite that can kill several species of ducks if ingested. Thousands of ducks were killed by these parasites during the falls of 2007 and 2008. Emerald shiners (often used as bait) are not native and were first sampled in 2005. Juvenile zebra mussel (veliger), were discovered while sampling for plankton in 2012. No adults were found during the summer of 2012. Each of these invasive species were likely introduced through human activities.

This special assessment contains data from 8 mid-lake gill net sets that were established in 1997. Mid-lake gill nets were set to augment summer near-shore sampling. These nets were initially set to determine if catch rate and growth statistics for various fish species were similar to those of the 24 near-shore gill net sets, and were set in conjunction with the 24 near-shore sets.

The summer gill netting portion of this survey will be discontinued in 2018 and replaced with fall (September) gill netting. Summer netting was developed prior to availability of GPS. Due to this, most nets were set in near shore shallow water. Much of the Winnie fish populations utilize off shore habitat. Fall gill netting has been completed annually since 2007. Fall sampling locations were developed to sample shallow, mid-depth, and deep habitat in proportion to its availability. This should result in catch rates that are relatively unbiased. As zebra mussel have become established, and water clarity has improved, fall gill net catch rates of walleye have increased in deep water habitat.

Walleye; Walleye catch rates typically vary similarly to near-shore, however, some years see gill net catch rates moving in opposite directions. That was the case in 2017 as near-shore catch for Walleye declined while mid-lake gill net catch increased from 4.0 per net to 4.4 per net. Mid-lake sampled Walleye varied from 12.8 to 23.3 inches with a mean length of 18.9 inches. The 2013 year class was dominant, making up 37 percent of the gill net catch. Catch rates for the 2012, 2014, and 2016 year classes were low.

The catch per gill net of Walleye longer than 19 inches has been used as an indicator of quality for the Walleye population. As with gill net catch rates, the catch of Walleye longer than 19 inches was lower in near-shore nets than mid-lake nets. The mean catch of Walleye longer than 19 inches sampled per mid-lake net since 1997 was 1.27 per net. This catch rate was similar to the mean catch of 1.19 Walleye longer than 19 inches per near-shore gill net set since 1997. The catch rate of Walleye longer than 19 inches of 1.9 per mid-lake net in 2017 far exceeded the catch of 1.1 per near-shore net.

Northern Pike; Mid-lake gill net catches of Northern Pike (pike) are typically less than near-shore nets, and that was the case in 2017. Reduced catch rates in mid-lake gill nets is likely due to sampling locations associated with open water vs vegetation. Gill net catch rates of pike in mid-lake nets decreased from 2013 through 2016. That trend reversed in 2017 with a new historic high catch of 9.5 pike per net. Pike sampled in 2017 varied from 16.9 to 34.1 inches with a mean length of 22.5 inches.

Yellow Perch; Yellow Perch (perch) have typically been sampled at a higher rate in mid-lake nets than from near shore nets. Results of the 2017 assessment followed that trend, with a catch rate of 63.3 per net in mid-lake net compared to 49.7 per near-shore net. The mean catch per gill net since 1997 has been higher in mid-lake gill nets (80.8) than near-shore gill nets (69.9). Although catch rates have been higher in mid-lake nets, unlike Walleye, the catch per gill net lift has varied similarly between near-shore and mid-lake gill nets. Perch sampled in mid-lake nets varied from 5.6 to 11.3 inches with a mean length of 7.1 inches.

Relative health of the perch population has been described by the percent of perch longer than nine inches in the gill net catch. The catch of perch longer than 9 inches (large perch) in near-shore gill nets declined to 6% in the early 1990's driven by high angler harvest. Declining catch rates of large perch in Lake Winnibigoshish and other lakes prompted a statewide change in the perch bag limit to 20 daily and 40 in possession in 2001. Strong year classes, and reduced harvest resulted in high catch rates of large perch in the early 2000's. The catch of large perch started to decline in 2004 and has declined from 45.9% in 2004 to 11.5% in 2015. The catch rate of 7.2% longer than 9 inches in 2016 was the lowest observed for mid-lake gill netting. Decreased percent of large perch is likely due to high recruitment that resulted in a high overall catch rate. As these young perch mature, the percent of large perch should increase. Perch longer than 9 inches were somewhat more abundant in 2017 with 7.5% of the gill net catch longer than 9 inches.

The Lake Winnibigoshish assessment is completed annually to track changes in abundance and growth of all game species. The assessment season begins with seining in July. The goal of seining is to sample young game and non-game species (including minnows) and to track growth of age 0 walleye and perch. Gill netting is conducted in July to sample game and non-game species age 1 and older. Abundance, growth rates, presence of parasites etc. is determined from this data. Trawling is conducted in August to continue tracking growth rates of age-0 walleye and perch. Trawling gives us the first clue to abundance of age-0 walleye and perch for that year. Temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles are taken from June through August and water chemistry analysis is done in August to track changes in the system that may affect the ability of some species to prosper or exist in the lake.

Walleye
Gill nets
Walleye were sampled at a rate of 4.9 per net, which was average for Lake Winnibigoshish. Walleye sampled varied from 6.7 to 26.3 inches with a mean length of 15.0 inches and mean weight of 1.3 pounds. The walleye population appeared to be healthy with most age classes sampled between age 1 and 12. Year-class strength was computed for walleye between age 2 and 7. Three average year classes (2003, 2004, and 2007), and three strong year classes ( 2002, 2005 and 2006) were sampled. However, none of the strong year classes were exceptionally strong. Mean back-calculated growth was similar to the Lake Winnibigoshish and statewide average for all ages, attaining 17.3 inches after five growing seasons.

Seine and trawl
Slow spring warming and below average summer temperatures appear to have resulted in some of the slowest growth observed since 1983. The shortened growing season resulted in smaller than average age-0 walleye. Slow growth and small size of age-0 walleye usually results in a weak year class.

Relatively few age-0 walleye were sampled by seine in 2009. Seine catch rates have not correlated to ultimate year-class strength for walleye in Lake Winnibigoshish. Growth rate of age-0 walleye has been a better predictor of year-class strength. Weekly mean lengths of age-0 walleye varied from 2.5 inches to 3.1 inches from July 1 to July 31.

Mean trawl catch rates for age-0 walleye were high when compared to catch rates observed since 1972. However, many of the age-0 walleye were sampled from one location. Age-0 walleye growth recorded through the first week of August was the slowest observed since 1983, reaching a mean length of 3.8 inches on August 8. Slow growth of age 0 walleye nearly always results in a weak year class of walleye.

Yellow perch
Gill nets
Yellow perch (perch) are an important species for anglers and as a prey item for walleye and northern pike. The catch of perch in assessment nets reached an historic low in 2005, largely due to poor year classes in 2000 and 2002. Strong year classes were produced in 2003 and 2005. Catch rates of perch have slowly increased as the strong 2003 and 2005 year classes have matured. As these year classes continue to mature, abundance and size structure should continue to improve. However, the 2006 year class also appears to be weak which may reduce the rate of recovery.

Perch were captured at a rate of 52.8 per net in 2009. This catch rate was lower than average for lake Winnibigoshish. Perch sampled varied from 4.1 to 11.6 inches with a mean length of 7.3 inches and mean weight of 0.20 pounds. Age classes 2 through 8 were sampled by gill net. An index of year-class strength was computed for ages 3 through 7. The 2004 year class was average, the 2002 and 2006 year classes were weak, and the 2003 and 2005 year classes were strong. As the 2003 and 2005 year classes continue to mature, abundance and size structure should improve. The catch was biased towards younger perch with 73% of the catch made up of age 2 through age 4 fish. Growth was relatively slow through age 2, then increased to average from age 3 to age 10. Perch grew to a mean length of 9.4 inches at age 6.

Relative health of the perch population has been described by the percent longer than 9 inches in the gill net catch. As perch catch rates decreased during the mid 1990's, the proportion of large perch (longer than 9 inches) increased. The proportion of large perch peaked as gill net catch rates fell below the first quartile. In 2005, the proportion of large perch sampled in near-shore gill nets declined for the first time since 1998. The proportion of perch longer than nine inches was stable in 2005 and 2006 at 16.9 percent, then declined to 9.8% as young perch were recruited to the fishery in 2007. Many small fish remain in the population, and the proportion of perch longer than 9 inches continues to be low at 10.4%.
The microsporidian parasite heterosporis has been documented in Lake Winnibigoshish yellow perch. No evidence of heterosporis was observed in 2009.

Seine and trawl
Catch rates of age-0 perch were near average for both seine and trawl. No correlation is evident between catch rates of age-0 yellow perch and ultimate year-class strength.

Northern pike

Catch rates of northern pike increased from 1999 through 2005 and exceeded the third quartile in five of the last eight years. The northern pike catch rates increased to 10.0 per gill net in 2009. Pike sampled varied from 9.3 to 30.6 inches with a mean length of 20.5 inches. All age classes from 1 to 7 were sampled by gill net. Age two, three, and four pike were most abundant, and contributed 92% of the catch. Growth rates were similar to the statewide mean through all ages achieving an avearge length of 24 inches at age 5.

Only two pike longer than 30 inches were sampled in this assessment. This does not mean that they are not present in the system, but it is an indication that their abundance has decreased. The decrease in size structure can be attributed to several causes. Cisco abundance has declined (cisco are preferred prey that provides more energy than other similar size prey), this may lead to slower growth rates. Conditions for reproduction and survival have been good, this may lead to increased density and more competition for food, which can also cause decreased growth. Angler harvest can have a large impact on the size structure of a pike population. This is also one of few factors that people have any control over. When anglers harvest the largest fish they catch, they can cause a slow decrease in the size structure of the fish they are harvesting. This occurs because fish are removed faster than other fish can grow to replace them. Considering the current size structure, anglers should release all pike longer than 25 inches, which should result in those fish growing closer to their potential and increase the chance to catch large pike.

Cisco

The gill net catch rate of 11.4 cisco per net in 2009 was similar to the catch rate in 2008. Catch rates for both years were below the 1st quartile and close to the historic minimum. The cisco population has been lower than average in 8 of the last 10 years. This is likely due to warmer than average fall water temperatures that may affect reproduction combined with occasional summer kills. Cisco sampled in 2008 varied from 6.4 to 17.1 inches with a mean length of 9.4 inches.


Water Quality

Water samples were taken on August 3, 2009. Physical and chemical parameters measured were within the range observed since 1983. Seven temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken between June 24 and August 3, 2009. Dissolved oxygen stratification was evident from July 6, through July 13. No evidence of thermal stratification was found in 2009. Thermal and dissolved oxygen stratification may result during periods of high air temperatures and low wind. When wind speeds increase to moderate levels (15 mph) the entire water column appears to mix.

Invasive Aquatic Species

Species that have been introduced through human activities to a location where they don't naturally occur are termed "invasive". Some invasive species are not necessarily harmful, but others cause ecological or economic problems.

Several invasive species have been introduced into Winnie. Three species of snail: banded mystery, Chinese mystery, and faucet have become established since 2000. Both species of mystery snail appear to be benign at this time. The faucet snail carries a trematode parasite that can kill several species of duck if ingested. Thousands of ducks were killed by these parasites during the falls of 2007 and 2008. Emerald shiners (often used as bait) are not native to Winnie, and were first sampled in 2005. Each of these invasive species were likely introduced through human activities.

The movement of any type of equipment (boats, boat trailers, boat lifts, docks, personal watercraft, bait containers, etc.) between lakes may transfer invasive species if precautions are not taken. To avoid being an accomplice to the spread of these unwanted species, people should make sure all equipment is thoroughly cleaned before moving it to a new body of water. More information about invasive species is available from the Minnesota DNR website.

The Lake Winnibigoshish assessment is completed annually to track changes in abundance and growth of fish species, and physical and chemical characteristics of the lake. The assessment season starts with seining and gill netting in late June to early July. The goal of seining is to sample young game and non-game species (including minnows) and to track growth of age 0 walleye and perch. Gill netting is conducted from late June through July to sample game and non-game species age 1 and older. Abundance, growth rates, maturity, presence of parasites etc. is determined from this data. Trawling is conducted in August to continue tracking growth rates of age-0 walleye and perch. Trawling gives us the first clue to abundance of age-0 walleye and perch for that year. Temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles are taken from June through August and water chemistry analysis is done in August to track changes in the system that may affect the ability of some species to prosper or exist in the lake.


Walleye
Gill nets
Walleye were sampled at a rate of 5.9 per net, which was above average for Lake Winnibigoshish. Walleye sampled varied from 7.3 to 26.2 inches with a mean length of 15.1 inches and mean weight of 1.3 pounds. The walleye population appeared to be healthy with most age classes sampled between age 1 and 13. Year-class strength was computed for walleye between age 2 and 7. Three average year classes (2003, 2004, and 2007), and two strong year classes (2005 and 2006) were sampled. Preliminary data suggests the 2008 year class may be weak. The last weak walleye year class for Lake Winnibigoshish was in 2000. Mean back-calculated growth was similar to the Lake Winnibigoshish and statewide average for all ages, attaining 17.8 inches after five growing seasons.

Seine and trawl
Relatively few age-0 walleye were sampled by seine in 2010. Seine catch rates have not correlated to ultimate year-class strength for walleye in Lake Winnibigoshish. Growth of age-0 walleye has been a better predictor of year-class strength. Early spring warming and normal summer temperatures appear to have resulted in some of the fastest growth observed since 1983. Weekly average lengths of age-0 walleye sampled by seining varied from 3.0 inches to 4.7 inches from July 3 to July 31.

Mean trawl catch rates for age-0 walleye were average when compared to catch rates observed since 1972. However, many of the age-0 walleye were sampled from one location. Age-0 walleye growth recorded through the first week of August was the second fastest observed since 1983, reaching a mean length of 5.0 inches on August 8. Fast growth of age 0 walleye usually results in a strong year class.


Walleye Experimental Regulation

The 17 to 26 inch protected slot limit for walleye was evaluated during the summer of 2010. Evaluation of the regulation showed that the fishery responded well to the regulation and that either the current 17 to 26 inch regulation, or a 18 to 26 inch protected slot with a bag limit of six fish would likely maintain the fishery at a healthy level. Results of the evaluation were open to public review in the fall of 2010 and public meetings were held at three locations in October. Two hundred forty seven comments were received through the public review period and meetings. Comments came from anglers varying from Baudette to Winona in Minnesota and eight other states from Wisconsin to Texas and Arizona. More than 85% of the comments favored either the 17 to 26 inch or 18 to 26 inch protected slots with a small advantage to the 17 to 26 inch slot. Of those favoring these two options, more than 1/3 agreed with either regulation. The final decision was to keep the 17 to 26 inch protected slot limit with a bag limit of six fish. This regulation was biologically suited to Lake Winnibigoshish and was viewed favorably by the majority of anglers.


Yellow perch
Gill nets
Yellow perch (perch) are an important species for anglers and as a prey item for walleye and northern pike. The catch of perch in assessment nets reached an historic low in 2005, largely due to poor year classes in 2000 and 2002. A strong year class was produced in 2003. Assessment catch rates have slowly increased as the strong 2003 year class has matured. As this year class continues to mature, abundance and size structure should continue to improve. The 2006 year class also appears to be weak which may reduce the rate of recovery.

Perch were captured at a rate of 54.9 per net in 2010, which was lower than average for Lake Winnibigoshish. Perch sampled varied from 5.0 to 11.2 inches with a mean length of 7.4 inches and mean weight of 0.21 pounds. Age classes 2 through 8 were sampled by gill net. An index of year-class strength was computed for ages 3 through 7. The 2005 and 2007 year classes were average, the 2004 and 2006 year classes were weak, and the 2003 year class was strong. As the 2003 year class has matured, size structure has slowly improved. The catch of perch in 2010 was biased towards younger individuals with 86% of the catch made up of age-3 through age-5 fish. Growth was relatively slow through age 2, then increased to average from age 3 to age 9. Perch grew to an average length of 9.1 inches at age 6.

Relative health of the yellow perch population can be described by the percent of perch longer than 9 inches in the gill net catch. The catch of large perch declined to 6% in the early 1990's driven by high harvest rates. Changes in Lake Winnibigoshish and other lakes prompted a statewide change in the perch bag limit to 20 daily and 40 in possession in 2001. Several strong year classes were produced during the same time period and the assessment catch of perch longer than 9 inches increased to 30% in 2004. In 2005, the proportion of large perch sampled declined for the first time since 1998. The proportion of perch longer than nine inches was 17% in 2005 and 2006, then declined to 9.8% in 2007 as young perch were recruited to the fishery. Although many small fish remain in the population, the strong 2003 year class has grown large enough to affect the proportion of perch longer than 9 inches. Twelve percent of the perch sampled were longer than 9 inches in 2010.

The microsporidian parasite heterosporis has been documented in Lake Winnibigoshish yellow perch. No evidence of heterosporis was observed in 2010.


Seine and trawl
Catch rates for age-0 perch of 226 per seine haul and 6,928 per hour of trawling were average for both seine and trawl. Growth of age 0 perch was faster than average with a mean length of 2.2 inches in mid August. No correlation is evident between trawl catch rates or growth of age-0 perch and year-class strength.


Northern pike
Catch rates of northern pike increased from 1999 through 2005 and exceeded the third quartile in five of the last eight years. The northern pike catch rate decreased to 7.3 per gill net in 2010 from 10.0 in 2009. Pike sampled varied from 14.9 to 35.0 inches with a mean length of 21.6 inches. All age classes from 1 to 7 and 9 were sampled by gill net. The 2007 and 2008 year classes were most abundant and contributed over 60% of the catch. Growth rates were similar to the statewide mean through all ages.

Although the size structure for pike increased in 2010 only five pike longer than 30 inches were sampled. The increase in size structure can be attributed to several causes. Cisco abundance has increased (cisco are preferred prey that provides more energy than other similar size prey), which may lead to faster growth rates. Reduced abundance is also beneficial to the pike population since increased pike density can cause more competition for food and space which may lead to decrease growth.

Although pike size structure has improved, further improvement is achievable. Angler harvest can have a large impact on the size structure of a pike population. This is also one of few factors people have any control over. When anglers harvest the largest fish they catch, they can cause a decrease in the size structure of the fish they are harvesting. This occurs because fish are removed faster than other fish can grow to replace them. Anglers can help increase the number of quality size pike in the population by releasing fish between 24 and 32 inches. This will allow pike the time to grow closer to their potential, and increase the chance of catching 8 to 10 pound fish.


Cisco
Cisco are a primary prey for muskellunge, pike and walleye. Growth rates of these species can be reduced if cisco are not present in the system. The gill net catch of 21.7 cisco per net in 2010 was nearly double the catch of 11.4 per net in 2009 and was near the historic average. The cisco population was lower than average for 8 of the last 10 years. This is likely due to warmer than average fall water temperatures that may affect reproduction combined with occasional summer kills. Cisco sampled in 2010 varied from 7.6 to 16.9 inches with a mean length of 11.0 inches.


Water Quality
Water samples were taken on August 2, 2010. Physical and chemical parameters measured were within the range observed since 1983. Six temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken between June 28 and August 11, 2010. Minor dissolved oxygen stratification was evident only on July 12. No evidence of thermal stratification was found in 2010. Thermal and dissolved oxygen stratification may result during periods of high air temperatures and low wind. When wind speeds increase to moderate levels (15 mph) the entire water column appears to mix. High wind speeds were common during the summer of 2010 which resulted in minimal oxygen stratification during the summer.


Invasive Aquatic Species
Species that have been introduced through human activities to a location where they don't naturally occur are termed "invasive". Some invasive species are not necessarily harmful, but others cause ecological or economic problems.

Several invasive species have been introduced into Winnie. Three species of snail: banded mystery, Chinese mystery, and faucet have become established since 2000. Both species of mystery snail appear to have no negative effect at this time. The faucet snail carries a trematode parasite that can kill several species of duck if ingested. Thousands of ducks were killed by these parasites during the falls of 2007 and 2008. Emerald shiners (often used as bait) are not native to Winnie, and were first sampled in 2005. Each of these invasive species were likely introduced through human activities.

The movement of any type of equipment (boats, boat trailers, boat lifts, docks, personal watercraft, bait containers, etc.) between lakes may transfer invasive species if precautions are not taken. To avoid being an accomplice to the spread of these unwanted species, people should make sure all equipment is thoroughly cleaned before moving it to a new body of water. More information about invasive species is available from the Minnesota DNR website.

This special assessment contains data from 8 mid-lake gill net sets that were first set in 1997. These nets were initially set to determine if catch rate and growth statistics for various fish species were similar to those of the 24 near-shore gill net sets and were set in conjunction with the 24 near-shore sets. After many years of sampling it appears that catch rate and size distribution can vary between the two net groups for Walleye, Northern Pike, and Yellow Perch while growth of fish appears to be similar.

Walleye; Walleye were sampled at a rate of 6.0 per net and varied from 8.0 to 24.2 inches with a mean length of 17.7 inches and mean weight of 2.0 pounds. The Walleye population appeared to be healthy with all age-classes sampled between age 1 and 11. Walleye year-class strength was computed for fish from age 1 to 7. One average year class (2011), three strong year classes (2009, 2010, and 2013), and two weak year classes (2012, and 2014) were sampled. The 2012 year class of Walleye continues to be as weak as any year class observed since the start of the large lake program. The 2014 year class has not fully recruited to the gill net, however, all indications are that it will be weak.

Average growth of Walleye was similar to the Lake Winnibigoshish and statewide average for all ages, attaining 17.7 inches after five growing seasons. However, growth of the 2012, 2013, and 2014 year classes was well above average for Lake Winnibigoshish. A 17 to 26 inch protected slot limit was in place between 2000 and 2014. During this time, age and length at maturity increased, spawning stock biomass increased, and overall abundance increased. This indicated that the Walleye population was likely fully recovered. Due to this, the protected slot limit was changed to 18 to 23 inches in 2015 so that anglers could utilize the harvestable surplus.

The average trawl catch rate of 1.9 age 0 Walleye per hour in 2016 was less than 3% of the long term average catch rate. Catch rates from 2013 through 2016 were the lowest seen since 1983. Increased water clarity was observed during this time period, which appears to affect trawl catch rates. Fish of many species were observed avoiding the boat during trawling. Due to this night electrofishing was conducted from late-August to late-September. Electrofishing catch rates for 2013 through 2015 indicated higher abundance than trawl catch rates would indicate. Electrofishing catch rates of age-0 Walleye were very low for trawling and electrofishing in 2016.

Electrofishing catch rates in 2016 were similar to those of trawling. Young of the year Walleye were sampled at a rate of 0 to 4 per hour (data available in the Grand Rapids Area Fisheries Office), and growth was good, reaching 7.2 inches in mid-September. Due to adverse weather conditions during September of 2016, electrofishing was conducted during less than ideal conditions that may have affected catch rates.

Yellow Perch; Perch are an important species to anglers and as a prey item for predators. Gill net catch rates were average or better in all assessments prior to 2003. However, gill net catch rates have only been average or better four times since 2003. The 2003-2016 average gill net catch of 58.6 has declined by 40% from the 1983 to 2003 average catch. Gill net catch rates of Walleye and Northern Pike (pike) have increased since 2000. Decreased gill net catch of perch may be a response to increased predation associated with increasing Walleye and pike density. If predator abundance remains high, perch abundance may find a new norm with a average catch near 60 per net.

Perch sampled in 2016 varied from 4.4 to 12.5 inches with a average length of 6.8 inches and weight of 0.16 pounds. Age-classes 2 through 10 were sampled by gill nets. An index of year-class strength was computed for year-classes sampled from 2009 through 2013. The 2011 and 2013 year-classes were weak while the 2009 and 2010 year-classes were average. The 2012 year class was strong. Natural mortality of perch increases at age 8 and few individuals live past age 10. The catch of perch in 2016 was primarily represented by younger individuals with nearly 85% of the catch made up of age 2 through age 4 fish. Although the perch population was composed primarily of small individuals, growth has not changed. Growth was relatively slow through age 2, then increased to average from age 3 to age 8. Perch grew to an average length of 8.9 inches at age 6.

Relative health of the perch population has been described by the percent of perch longer than 9 inches (large perch) in the gill net catch. The gill net catch of large perch declined to 5.5% in the early 1990's driven by high angler harvest. Changes in Lake Winnibigoshish and other lakes prompted a statewide change in the perch bag limit to 20 daily and 40 in possession in 2001. Several strong year classes were produced during the late 1980's and the gill net catch of large perch increased to 30% in 2004. Since that time there has been a gradual decline in the percent of large perch. The perch catch of 7.5% longer than 9 inches in 2016 was similar to 2015. Part of the decline in large perch may be due to increased predator numbers. Both Northern Pike and Walleye catch rates have increased as the catch of large perch has declined.

The trawl catch rate for age 0 perch of 11,940 per hour was similar to the long term average. Growth of age 0 perch was average with a mean length of 1.9 inches in mid-August. Clear water conditions that appear to have affected trawl catch rates of young of the year Walleye may also affected catch rates of young of the year perch. Few age 0 perch were sampled in trawl hauls less than 10 feet of water. Catch rates of age 0 perch were typically highest in less than 8 feet of water prior to clearing water. No correlation is evident between trawl catch rates or growth of age 0 perch and year-class strength.

The heterosporis parasite has been documented in Lake Winnibigoshish perch. No evidence of heterosporis was observed in perch during the 2016 population assessment, although anglers report the presence of heterosporis in a few perch each year.

Northern Pike; Catch rates of Northern Pike (pike) showed an increasing trend from 1994 through 2005, and were higher than average (between 7.5 and 9.6 per net) in four years between 2002 and 2009. The pike catch rate was relatively stable and similar to average between 2006 and 2011. Gill net catch rates increased dramatically between 2011 and 2014, reaching a new historic high of 14.1 per net in 2013. Pike catch rate in 2016 was average for the first time since 2011 at 9.0 pike per gill net.

Pike sampled in 2016 varied from 12.5 to 33.9 inches with a mean length of 21.7 inches. Mean length of pike typically declines as catch rates increase. As catch rates have decreased since 2013, average length has increased. Mean pike length of 21.7 inches in 2016 increased from 2015 and 2014, but was below the average of 21.9 inches. Age-classes from 1 through 7 were sampled by gill net. Growth rates were similar to the statewide average through all ages.

The number of pike longer than 30 inches has been used as an indication of quality in the pike population. More than 10 pike longer than 30 inches were sampled in all assessments between 1994 and 2000. This was an indication of a high quality pike population. Since that time there has been a decrease in quality pike to 2 or 3 pike longer than 30 inches in all assessments since 2013.

Decreased size structure may be attributed to several causes. Reproduction and recruitment were strong for the 2012, 2013, and 2014 year classes which made up 84% of the catch, and Cisco abundance decreased due to summer kill in 2012 (Cisco are preferred prey that provides more energy than other similar size prey). A strong prey base of Cisco may lead to faster pike growth rates. High angler harvest of pike may result in a recruitment response (increased reproduction to replace individuals removed from the system). Larger numbers of small pike vs smaller numbers of medium to large pike may cause reduced growth rates due to increased competition for food and space. The recent increase in catch rate may result in slower pike growth in the future. Fishers can help maintain the pike size structure by releasing, or not harvesting most pike longer than 22 inches.

Cisco; Cisco are a primary prey species for Muskellunge, pike, and Walleye. Growth rates of these species may be reduced if Cisco are not present in the system. The gill net catch of 4.1 per net in 2015 was the lowest since 1983. The historic low catch rate seen in 2015 was eclipsed in 2016 with a new historic low of catch rate of 2.6 Cisco per gill net. Cisco varied from 7.6 to 15.9 inches with a mean length of 10.6 inches. Cisco catch rates have been lower than average for 7 of the last 11 years. This is likely due to warmer than average summer and fall water temperatures that may affect reproduction and cause occasional summer kills. Water temperatures were warm during the summer of 2012 and caused a summer kill of Cisco. Summer kill of Cisco has been an irregular occurrence at Lake Winnibigoshish. It is normal for the population to decline following a summer kill, however, the population typically recovers several years following the summer kill. The Cisco population currently shows no signs of recovery.

Water Quality; Five temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken between June 22 and August 12, 2016. Dissolved oxygen stratification was evident on July 25 and August 23. No evidence of thermal stratification was found in 2016. Thermal and dissolved oxygen stratification may result during periods of high air temperatures and low wind. When wind speeds increase to moderate levels (15 mph) the entire water column appears to mix.

Water chemistry measurements have been recorded for most years since 1983. Water clarity as measured by Secchi disc in 2016 of 8.0 feet was lower than the past several years. Recent increases in water clarity may be related to the introduction of filter feeding faucet snails around 2000. Faucet snails were dispersed throughout the system by 2008. Zebra Mussel are now established and likely will contribute to clear water.

Invasive Aquatic Species; Invasive species are species that are not native to Minnesota and cause economic or environmental harm or harm to human health. Non-native species are not native to Minnesota but don't cause economic or environmental harm or harm to human health. All are illegal to introduce into or move between state waters. Several species have been introduced into Lake Winnibigoshish. Three species of snail: Banded Mystery, Chinese Mystery, and Faucet have become established since 2000. Both species of mystery snail appear to have no negative effect at this time. The Faucet Snail carries a trematode parasite that can kill several species of ducks if ingested. Thousands of ducks were killed by these parasites during the falls of 2007 and 2008. The Faucet Snail is a filter feeder and may be responsible for clearing water prior to the introduction of Zebra Mussel.

Juvenile Zebra Mussels (veliger) were discovered while sampling zooplankton during the summer of 2012. No zebra mussel veliger were found while sampling for zooplankton in 2013. Zebra Mussel veliger have been sampled each year since 2013. Near-shore areas of hard substrate were inspected for adult Zebra Mussel each year since 2012, and divers have inspected likely offshore areas since 2014. No adults were discovered until 2016. Adults were found on near-shore driftwood in the early summer, then found by divers on mid-lake rock structure during August. Sampling for Zebra Mussels veliger will continue and the spread of adults will continue to be documented.

Starry Stonewort (an algae) was discovered in Cass Lake during the summer of 2016. This discovery upstream of Lake Winnibigoshish prompted an investigation on Lake Winnibigoshish. Starry Stonewort was discovered along the south and west shores of the lake and appears to have been established for several years.

Emerald Shiners (often used as bait) are not native to Winnie, were first sampled in 2005, and have been sampled each year since. Each of these invasive species were likely introduced through human activities. Rusty Crayfish are present in Cass Lake, and curly leaf pondweed is present in Dixon Lake. Both of these lakes are upstream of Lake Winnibigoshish. Introduction to Lake Winnibigoshish in the near future is likely.

Movement of any type of equipment (boats, boat trailers, boat lifts, docks, personal watercraft, bait containers, etc.) between lakes may transfer invasive species if precautions are not taken. To avoid being an accomplice to the spread of these unwanted species, people should ensure that all equipment is thoroughly cleaned and dried before moving it to a new body of water. More information regarding invasive species is available at www.dnr.state.mn.us/invasives/index.html

Lake Winnibigoshish is part of the Mississippi River headwaters reservoir system, and is located 15 miles northwest of Deer River, Minnesota. The lake is a large, shallow, wind-swept reservoir with a sandy shoreline and gently sloping shoal areas. Winnibigoshish has a surface area of 58,544 acres, mean depth of 15.1 feet, littoral area of 20,490 acres (35%), and a maximum depth of 66 feet. Water clarity has dramatically increased following the introduction of Zebra Mussels in 2012, yet clarity continues to vary seasonally.

Lake Winnibigoshish has been managed as part of the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources (DNR) large lake program since 1983. Management activities include special fishing regulations, fish stocking, occasional creel surveys, and annual fish surveys. Annual fall gill netting has been conducted since 2007 using 32 nets. Fall electrofishing has also been conducted since 2018 to evaluate Walleye production.

A large annual Walleye spawning operation is conducted at Little Cut Foot Sioux Lake, which is a large connected flowage. The operational plan includes 10% of the egg take put back as fry. The relative contribution from these stockings is difficult to interpret due to the lack of non-stocked years. Walleye harvest has been regulated with a special regulation since 2000. The regulation was modified in 2015 to an 18 to 23 inch protected slot length (PSL) with one over in possession to allow some additional harvest of larger fish.

Winnibigoshish is considered a high profile Walleye lake with a lot of effort directed towards the management of the species. Gill net catches have been variable with a decreasing trend. However, a recent uptick has been observed. Variability in Walleye catches are often associated with cycles in recruitment, described as year class strength. This trait is common on natural Walleye lakes and has been observed on Winnibigoshish. Recent surveys show a period of low recruitment from 2014 to 2017, while 2018 and 2019 appear to be stronger. The 2020 Walleye catch was the third highest observed in fall netting. However, the catch was largely driven by a high proportion of age-1 and -2 fish. Age-2 fish had an average length of 12.5 inches in the fall of 2020. This suggests favorable angling opportunities for the next few years as these fish continue to grow.

Winnibigoshish is known to maintain a quality size distribution of Walleye, but the protected slot has limited harvest at times. Limited harvest was a product of reduced recruitment in recent years due to longer gaps between stronger year classes. The last strong year class was 2013 which was a large contributor to angler success. These fish were age-7 in 2020, with an average length of 22 inches and comprised 5% of the overall catch. Protected slot length fish comprised 17% of the sample in 2020. About one third of the slot length fish were from the 2013 year class. Walleye had an average length of 13 inches in 2020 with fish up to 26 inches. The low average length is a function of the disproportionately high catches of ages-1 and -2.

Walleye age analysis identified ages 0 to 15 in the sample, and sex and maturity determination indicated a relatively even distribution between males and females. Both were similar to past surveys and suggests a balanced population. Other population exploitation indicators like female spawning stock biomass (SSB), female length at 50% maturity and female age at 50% maturity were within the expected range, similar to past surveys and indicative of a balanced population. The female fall SSB estimate was 1.7 lbs./acre and half the females were mature at 17.7 inches and 3.1 years in 2020. Walleye growth rates have been favorable on Winnibigoshish, typically exceeding statewide averages. Male and female growth rates diverge between ages-3 and -4. By age-4, male Walleye averaged 16 inches while females averaged 17.2 inches in 2020.

Winnibigoshish is a destination Yellow Perch fishery with a history of producing large fish. Perch over 11 inches are regularly sampled. Perch greater than eight inches are considered quality size and greater than 50% of this size perch are harvested by both summer and winter anglers. The catch for eight inch and greater perch has averaged 8.4/net and the proportion has averaged 34% since 2007. Yellow Perch exceeding eight inches were sampled at a rate of 5.7/net and comprised 35% of the sample in 2020. This suggests roughly one third of perch caught while angling will be of a size anglers elect to harvest.

Yellow Perch are an important prey species besides being popular with anglers. The 2020 catch was typical for lakes with similar habitats, but below average for Winnie. The fall catches have been variable. Unevenness in fall catches is likely attributed to variability in recruitment, angling pressure and sampling conditions. Age analysis identified ages 1 to 9 present. Growth was similar to statewide averages and past surveys. Perch growth rates begin to diverge between age-2 and -3. Length at capture suggest perch begin to reach a harvestable size by age 5. By age-5, male perch averaged 7.7 inches while females averaged 8.3 inches in 2020.

Northern Pike are another popular species with anglers and are well suited for Winnibigoshish and connected waters. Winnibigoshish tends to have higher pike abundance than comparable lakes, and catches have been relatively stable in fall surveys. Lengths ranged from 15.1 to 28.8 inches with an average of 22.8 inches in 2020. The length frequency was similar to previous fall surveys. However, fish over 30 inches have been observed in every survey except 2020. It is believed harvest has likely influenced size quality. Winnibigoshish lies within the North-central Zone. Since 2018, lakes within this zone have had a Northern Pike protected slot length regulation from 22 to 26 inches, a bag limit of 10 fish but only two can be greater then 26 inches. Spearing has an exception of one fish in the PSL. In 2020, 43% of the catch was within the pike PSL, compared to 41% and 35% observed in 2019 and 2018.

Sex and maturity determinations for Northern Pike show a little over half were female and very few were immature. Age analysis indicated ages 1 to 6 present, with relatively consistent recruitment. Age, sex and maturity determinations were similar to past surveys. The proportion of pike older than age 4 was low, comprising only 10%. Age-4 pike averaged over 25 inches at the time of capture. Anglers and spear fishers are encouraged to take advantage of the expanded harvest opportunities offered by the North-central Zone regulation, but limit their take of fish over 22 inches to help improve size structure. Pike growth was favorable, exceeding statewide averages and was similar to past surveys. Male and female growth rates diverge between ages 1 and 2. Age-2 males averaged 15.3 inches while females averaged 17.1 inches, in 2020.

Cisco are an important prey species and an indicator species due to their environmental sensitivity. Catches have been variable, which is often associated with pelagic species like Cisco, but have had a declining trend over the past decade. Warmer water temperatures and Zebra Mussel infestations are two factors that have likely influenced this trend. Cisco lengths ranged from 7.2 to 16.3 inches with an average of 11.5 inches. Length frequency had a multimodal distribution. Scale and otolith analysis identified ages 1,2, and 4 to 8 present. Half of the Cisco sampled were age 1 and averaged 7.9 inches at the time of capture. Ages 4 to 8 had lengths within a relatively narrow band from 13 to 16 inches.

Other species sampled include Burbot, Largemouth Bass, Rock Bass, Shorthead Redhorse, Silver Redhorse, White Sucker and Yellow Bullhead.

Winnibigoshish has had several exotic or non-native species introduced in the last 20 years. Banded Mystery and Chinese Mystery snails were first noted around 2000, followed by Faucet Snails. A trematode parasite associated with Faucet Snails was responsible for a large diver duck die-off in 2007 and 2008. Lesser die-offs have occurred almost annually since.

Juvenile Zebra Mussels (veligers) were discovered while sampling zooplankton in 2012. Adults were found on driftwood in 2016 and subsequent investigations found adults were present on nearly all firm structure by 2017. Recent zooplankton sampling suggest veliger density has decreased slightly.

Zebra Mussels and Faucet Snails have contributed to ecosystem changes. Both are effective filter feeders and are responsible for a large increase in water clarity. These species shunt nutrients to the benthic portion of the lake resulting in large filamentous algae mats. Decreased nutrient availability within the water column has changed species compositions and densities of phytoplankton, zooplankton and aquatic invertebrates. The impact of Zebra Mussels on the fish community is less apparent and unclear at this time. However, Winnibigoshish has been fully infested for only four seasons to date. Zebra Mussels have influenced angler use. With the increased water clarity, the traditional mid-day Walleye bite has shifted to a more crepuscular event.

Starry Stonewort was discovered upstream in Cass Lake in 2016. Subsequent sampling found it along the south and west shores of Winnibigoshish, and it appeared to have been established for several years. It has been reported along the east shore in 2017, near Birches public access.

Emerald Shiners ae not native to Winnibigoshish and were first sampled in 2015. This species is often used as bait and has been sampled while seining since. Rusty Crayfish and curly leaf pondweed are found in upstream connected waters and it is assumed introduction is likely.

Each of these introductions have occurred through human activities. Movement of any type of equipment that can trap or hold contaminated water, plant fragments or aquatic organisms can be a potential vector of spread if precautions are not taken. To avoid being an accomplice to the spread of these unwanted species, people should ensure that all equipment is thoroughly cleaned and dried before moving it to a new body of water. More information is available at https://www.dnr.state.mn.us/invasives/ais/index.html.

Thirty one gillnets were set during the last two weeks of September, 2010. This was the fourth consecutive year of fall sampling. The goals of this netting were: 1 - develop a population estimate of adult walleye using available walleye population models, and 2 - build on the long term data set of fall netting so that fall netting can eventually replace summer netting as the annual index of abundance for primary fish species in Lake Winnibigoshish. Fall gillnet catch rates for walleye followed the trend of higher catch rates (2 to 3X) than the summer gillnet catch. While perch and northern pike catch rates were consistently lower than the summer nets. Cisco catch rates have varied, some years having higher catch rates in the summer, while fall catch rates were higher on other years. Data from this survey should not be used to evaluate Lake Winnibigoshish fish populations, or to compare between years within lake or between different lakes.

Lake Winnibigoshish is sampled annually to track changes in abundance and growth of fish species, and physical and chemical characteristics of the lake. The assessment season typically starts with seining and gill netting in late June to early July. The goal of seining is to sample young game and non-game species (including minnows) and to track growth of age 0 Walleye and Yellow Perch (perch). Gill netting is conducted from late June through July to sample game and non-game species age 1 and older. Abundance, growth rates, maturity, presence of parasites etc. is determined from these data. Trawling is conducted in August to continue tracking growth rates of age 0 Walleye and perch. Trawling gives us the first clue to abundance of age 0 Walleye and perch for that year. Temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles are taken from June through August and water chemistry analysis is completed in August to track changes in the system that may affect the ability of some species to prosper or exist in the lake. Plankton sampling was included in standard sampling beginning in 2012 and were continued in 2013. Five samples were taken on seven dates for a total of 35 samples in 2013. These samples were collected to determine baseline planktonic species composition.

Walleye; Walleye were sampled at a rate of 6.6 per net (Figure 1). Walleye sampled varied from 11.2 to 28.8 inches with a mean length of 17.1 inches and mean weight of 1.8 pounds. The Walleye population generally appeared to be healthy with most age-classes sampled between age 2 and 13. Year-class strength was computed for Walleye between age 2 and 7. Two average year-classes (2007, and 2011), three strong year-classes (2006, 2009, and 2010), and one weak year-class (2008) were sampled (Figure 2). Mean back-calculated growth was similar to the Lake Winnibigoshish and statewide average for all ages, attaining 17.4 inches after five growing seasons. The 17 to 26 inch protected slot limit has been in place since 2000. During this time, age and length at maturity has increased from a low of 14.6 inches and 3.2 years to 17.2 inches and 4.2 years (Figures 3 and 4). Spawning stock biomass has increased from 0.5 to 2.7 pounds per acre (Figure 5). This may indicate that the Walleye population has fully recovered from a period of high harvest and reduced recruitment between the mid 1980's and mid 1990's.

The mean trawl catch rate of 5.5 Walleye per hour was the lowest observed since 1983, however, low catch rates may not result in low abundance of that year-class. For example, the trawl catch rate of 20.5 young of the year Walleye per hour in 2005 resulted in an above average year-class. An important factor in year-class strength is growth of those fish during their first year. Young of the year Walleye growth for trawl sampled fish was far below average in 2013. Low catch rates can be explained by extremely clear water during the summer of 2013. Fish of many species were observed avoiding the boat during trawling. Due to this (and to collect samples for the "Walleye Fry Stocking in Egg-Take Lakes" project) night electrofishing was conducted during August. Results of electrofishing were counter to those of trawling. Walleye were sampled at a rate of 88 per hour (data available in the Grand Rapids Area Fisheries Office) and growth was faster than average when compared to historic trawl growth rates. Fast growth of age 0 Walleye often results in a strong year class.

Yellow Perch; Perch are an important species to anglers and as a prey item for predators. The catch of perch in assessment nets reached a historic low (at the time) in 2005, largely due to poor year-classes in 2000 and 2002. A strong 2003 year-class moved through the system resulting in higher catch rates through 2007. Catch rates declined from 2007 through 2011 to a new historic low catch of 43.6 per net. The catch rate for perch increased to 57.5 per net in 2012 and increased again to 74.4 in 2013 (Figure 6). Sampled Perch varied from 5.0 to 11.0 inches with a mean length of 7.0 inches and mean weight of 0.2 pounds. Age-classes 3 through 7 were sampled by gill nets. An index of year-class strength was computed for all year-classes sampled from 2006 through 2010. The 2006 and 2007 year-classes were weak while the 2009 and 2010 year-classes were strong and the 2008 year-class was average (Figure 7). The 2010 year-class appeared to be the strongest since 2003. Natural mortality of perch increases at age 8 and few individuals live past age 10. The catch of perch in 2013 was primarily represented by younger individuals with 95% of the catch made up of age 3 through age 5 fish. Growth was relatively slow through age 2, then increased to average from age 3 to age 8. Perch grew to an average length of 9 inches at age 6.

Relative health of the perch population can be described by the percent of perch longer than nine inches in the gill net catch. The catch of large perch (longer than 9 inches) declined to 6% in the early 1990's driven by high angler harvest. Changes in Lake Winnibigoshish and other lakes prompted a statewide change in the perch bag limit to 20 daily and 40 in possession in 2001. Several strong year classes were produced during the same time period and the assessment catch of perch longer than nine inches increased to 30% in 2004. In 2005, the proportion of large perch sampled in near-shore gill nets declined for the first time since 1998. The proportion of perch longer than nine inches was about 17% in 2005 and 2006, then declined to 9.8% in 2007 as young perch were recruited to the fishery. No strong year classes were produced between 2003 and 2009. As a result the percent of perch longer than 9 inches fluctuated between 10% and 13% between 2007 and 2012. Strong year classes of perch were produced in 2009 and 2010. This resulted in increased catch rates (mostly young fish) and a reduced catch of perch longer than 9 inches (7.7%) in 2013 (Figure 8).

The catch rate for age 0 perch of 6,952 per hour of trawling was below average. Growth of age 0 perch was slower than average with a mean length of 1.8 inches in mid-August. The clear water conditions that appear to have affected trawl catch rates of young of the year Walleye likely affected catch rates of young of the year Yellow Perch also. No correlation is evident between trawl catch rates or growth of age 0 perch and year-class strength.

The microsporidian parasite heterosporis has been documented in Lake Winnibigoshish Yellow Perch. No evidence of heterosporis was observed in perch during the 2013 population assessment, although anglers report the presence of heterosporis in a few perch each year.

Northern Pike; Catch rates of Northern Pike (pike) showed an increasing trend from 1999 through 2005 and exceeded the third quartile (9.6 per net) in five years between 2002 and 2009. The pike catch rate decreased to 7.3 per gill net in 2010 from 10.0 in 2009 then rose to 8.5 in 2011 and was the third highest observed in 2012 at 10.3 per net. The gill net catch of 14.1 per net in 2013 was the highest observed (Figure 9). Pike sampled in 2013 varied from 13.0 to 32.6 inches with a mean length of 20.6 inches. Mean length of pike has been declining as catch rates have increased. Average pike length of 20.6 inches in 2013 was the lowest observed since 1983 (Figure 10). Age-classes from 1 to 5 were sampled by gill net. Growth rates were similar to the statewide mean through all ages.

Size structure of the pike population improved between 2010 and 2012. That trend was reversed in 2013 as a strong component of small young pike were recruited to the gill net catch. Only two pike longer than 30 inches were sampled in the 2013 assessment vs 10 in the 2011 and 9 in the 2012 assessments (Figure 11). Decreased size structure may be attributed to several causes. Reproduction and recruitment was strong for the 2010 and 2011 year classes which made up 74% of the catch, and Cisco abundance decreased due to summer kill in 2012 (Cisco are preferred prey that provides more energy than other similar size prey). A strong prey base of Cisco may lead to faster pike growth rates. High angler harvest of pike may result in a recruitment response (increased reproduction to replace individuals removed from the system). Larger numbers of small pike vs smaller numbers of medium to large pike may cause reduced growth rates due to increased competition for food and space. The recent increase in catch rate may result in slower pike growth in the future. Anglers can help maintain the pike size structure by releasing most pike longer than 25 inches and harvesting pike smaller than 24 inches.

Cisco; Cisco are a primary prey for Muskellunge, pike and Walleye. Growth rates of these species may be less if Cisco are not present in the system. The gill net catch of 8.6 per net in 2013 was the second lowest since 1983 and decreased by nearly 50 percent from the catch of 16.0 per net in 2012 (Figure 12). Cisco sampled varied from 6.0 to 15.5 inches with a mean length of 11.2 inches. Cisco catch rates were lower than average for 6 of the last 10 years. This is likely due to warmer than average summer and fall water temperatures that may affect reproduction and cause occasional summer kills. Summer water temperatures were warm during the summer of 2012 and caused a summer kill of Cisco. Effects of that summer kill were a likely cause of decreased catch rate in 2013.

Water Quality; Seven temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken between June 24 and August 13, 2013. Dissolved oxygen stratification was evident between June 24 and July 24. No evidence of thermal stratification was found in 2013. Thermal and dissolved oxygen stratification may result during periods of high air temperatures and low wind. When wind speeds increase to moderate levels (15 mph) the entire water column appears to mix.

Water chemistry measurements have been recorded for most years since 1983. Water clarity as measured by Secchi disc in 2013 was higher than in most years. Secchi disc measurement varies between 10.0 and 18.0 feet. The measurement on August 13 was 11.0 feet compared to the long term average of 7.0 feet. The Total Phosphorous concentration of 0.023 parts per million (ppm) in 2013 was within the recorded range of 0.015 to 0.051ppm, but was 30 percent lower than the long term mean of 0.030ppm.

Invasive Aquatic Species; Species that have been introduced through human activities to a location where they don't naturally occur are termed "invasive". Some invasive species are not necessarily harmful, but others cause ecological or economic problems. Several invasive species have been introduced to Lake Winnibigoshish. Three species of snail: banded mystery, Chinese mystery, and faucet have become established since 2000. Both species of mystery snail appear to have no negative effect at this time. The faucet snail carries a trematode parasite that can kill several species of ducks if ingested. Thousands of ducks were killed by these parasites during the falls of 2007 and 2008. Emerald shiners (often used as bait) are not native and were first sampled in 2005. Juvenile zebra mussel (veliger), were discovered while sampling for plankton in 2012. No zebra mussel veliger were found while sampling for zooplankton in 2013 No adults were found during 2012 or 2013 assessments. Each of these invasive species were likely introduced through human activities.

Thirty two gill nets were set during the last two weeks of September, 2014. This was the eighth consecutive year of fall sampling. The goals of this netting are: 1) develop a population estimate of adult walleye using available walleye population models, 2) determine accurate sex ratios and spawning stock biomass for the lake Winnibigoshish Walleye population, and 3) build on the long term data set of fall netting so that fall netting may eventually replace summer netting as the annual index of abundance for primary fish species in Lake Winnibigoshish.

Walleye
Near-shore gill nets
Walleye were sampled at a rate of 4.6 per net, which was average for Lake Winnibigoshish. Walleye sampled varied from 6.5 to 26.3 inches with a mean length of 14.8 inches and mean weight of 1.4 pounds. The walleye population appeared to be healthy with most age classes sampled between age 1 and 12. Year class strength was computed for walleye from age 2 to age 7. One weak year class (2000), four average year classes (1999, 2002, 2003, and 2004), and two strong year classes (2001 and 2005) were sampled. Walleye catch rates were near average for most length groups in 2007. Mean back-calculated growth was similar to the Lake Winnibigoshish and statewide average for all ages, attaining 17.4 inches after five growing seasons.

Seine and trawl
Relatively few age 0 walleye were sampled by seine in 2007. Seine catch rates have not correlated to ultimate year class strength for walleye in Lake Winnibigoshish. Growth rates of age 0 walleye has been a better predictor of year class strength. Rapid spring warming and above average summer temperatures appear to have resulted in faster than average growth and relatively large size of age-0 walleye. Fast growth and large size of fingerling walleye often correspond to strong year classes. Mean lengths of age 0 walleye varied from 3.3 to 4.4 inches from July 7 to July 30.

The mean trawl catch rate for age 0 walleye in 2007 was nearly double the highest catch rate observed since 1972. Age 0 walleye growth recorded through the first week of August was faster than mean growth since 1983, reaching a mean length of 4.7 inches on August 7. High trawl catch rates of age 0 walleye have not resulted in strong year classes, however, high catch rates combined with faster than average growth may result in above average abundance.

Yellow perch
Near-shore gill nets
Yellow perch were captured at a rate of 86.4 per net. This catch rate was considerably higher than the catch of 56.3 per net in 2006, and was near average for Lake Winnibigoshish. Perch sampled in 2007 varied from 2.3 to 11.7 inches with a mean length of 7.1 inches and mean weight of 0.18 pounds. Catch rates and size structure of sampled perch have changed recently. Catch rates started a slow decline in the late 1990s, but were within historic norms until 2003. Catch rates from 2003 through 2006 were below the first quartile for Lake Winnibigoshish due to weak 2000 and 2002 year classes. Catch rates recovered to average in 2007 due to increased abundance of small, young perch.

Age classes 1 through 8 were sampled by gill net. An index of yearclass strength was computed for ages 3 through 7. The 2001 and 2004 year classes were average, the 2000 and 2002 year classes were weak, and the 2003 year class was strong. The catch was heavily biased towards younger perch with 88% of the catch made up of age 2 through age 4 fish. Yellow perch growth was relatively slow through age 2, increased to near average from age 3 to age 9, with perch attaining a mean length of 9.2 inches at age 6.

Relative health of the yellow perch population has been described by the percent of perch longer than 9 inches in the gill net catch. As perch catch rates decreased the proportion of large perch (longer than 9 inches) increased. The proportion of large perch peaked as gill net catch rates fell below the first quartile. In 2005, the proportion of large perch sampled in near-shore gill nets declined for the first time since 1998. The proportion of perch longer than nine inches was stable in 2005 and 2006 at 16.9 percent, then declined to 9.8% in 2007 as young perch were recruited to the fishery.

The microsporidian parasite heterosporis has been documented in Lake Winnibigoshish yellow perch. Of 180 perch examined in 2007 no evidence of heterosporis was observed.

Seine and trawl
Catch rates of age-0 yellow perch were near average for both seine and trawl. No correlation is evident between catch rates of age-0 yellow perch and ultimate year-class strength.

Northern pike
Near-shore gill nets
Catch rates of northern pike increased from 1999 through 2005 and exceeded the third quartile in four of six years since 2002. Northern pike catch rates increased to 9.7 per near-shore gill net in 2007. Pike sampled in near-shore gill nets varied from 12.0 to 31.1 inches with a mean length of 21.0 inches. All age classes between age 1 and 8 were sampled by gill net. Age two, three, and four pike were most abundant and pike exhibited growth rates that were similar to state wide averages through all ages.


Cisco
Near-shore gill nets
Gill net catch rates of cisco were within historic bounds for both near-shore and mid-lake nets in 2007. The catch rate of 21.2 per near-shore net was near the first quartile. Cisco were not aged in 2007, however, examination of the length frequency indicates that at least one year class was poorly represented in the catch. Cisco sampled in near-shore gill nets varied from 6.6 to 16.5 inches with a mean length of 8.0 inches.

Water Quality
Water samples were taken on August 6, 2007. Physical and chemical parameters measured were within the range observed since 1983 . Five temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken from June 25 to July 23, 2007. Dissolved oxygen stratification was evident on July 5, July 9, and July 23. No evidence of thermal stratification was found in 2007. Thermal and dissolved oxygen stratification may result during periods of high air temperatures and low wind. When wind speeds increase to moderate levels (15 mph) the entire water column appears to mix.

Thirty two gill nets were set during the last two weeks of September, 2013. This was the seventh consecutive year of fall sampling. The goals of this netting are: 1 develop a population estimate of adult walleye using available walleye population models, and 2 build on the long term data set of fall netting so that fall netting may eventually replace summer netting as the annual index of abundance for primary fish species in Lake Winnibigoshish.

The gill net catch of 6.5 Walleye per net was the lowest observed since 2007. Summer catch rates have increased over time, while fall catch rates have been decreasing. Summer and fall catch rates were nearly identical in 2013. The trend of gill net catch rates moving in opposite directions makes comparison difficult.
