Size structure was good, with fish present from 6.8 to 25.1 inches. All ages of walleye between 0 and 15 were represented except 11, 13, and 14. An index of year class strength was computed for the 2006 through 2011 year classes. The 2009, 2010, and 2011 year classes were average, the 2006 and 2007 year classes were strong, and the 2008 year class was weak. No age one Walleye were sampled in summer near-shore or summer mid-lake nets. Five age one Walleye were sampled in fall gill nets.

Yellow Perch (perch) catch rates have varied from 17.5 to 38.5 since 2007. The catch rate of 18.2 per net in 2013 was similar to the 2012 catch rate of 19.9 per net. Perch varied from 3.3 to 11.6 inches with a mean length of 7.4 inches. Age classes 1 through 7 and 9 were sampled. Age two, three, and five were most frequently sampled. The proportion of perch longer than 9 inches has increased over the last two years. Sixteen percent of the 2012 fall captured perch and 18.4 percent of the 2013 sample were longer than 9 inches. Fall gill net catch rates continue to be lower than summer catch rates, and the percent of perch longer than 9 inches continues to be higher than summer near-shore netting. Neither of these appear to be explained by growth of perch between the two survey dates.

Northern pike (pike) were sampled at a rate of 4.8 per gill net. This catch rate is near the historic high since 2007 (range 3.0-4.9, mean 3.5). Pike length varied from 9.2 to 30.5 inches with a mean length of 21.6 inches. Pike age structure varied similarly to the summer assessment with ages one through seven represented. As with most Lake Winnibigoshish assessments, the majority of pike sampled were from the age two, three, and four cohorts.

The gill net catch of cisco decreased to a historic low of 8.2 per net in 2013 from the catch rate of 24.1 in 2011 and 13.9 in 2012. The decline in catch rate was expected due to continuing effects of a summer kill observed during the summer of 2012. Although the catch rate was low, cisco have shown the ability to recover from low catch rates in the past. Cisco length varied from 7.1 to 16.4 inches with a mean length of 12.1 inches.

A preliminary comparison of summer and fall walleye gill net catch rates was completed using the Qabg model and direct comparison early in 2012. Results of that modeling indicated that more years of sampling are required before summer catch rates can be predicted from the fall gill net catch. Catch rates will be evaluated periodically until variance between predicted and actual catch rates is acceptable.

Lake Winnibigoshish (Winnie) has a low-density native Muskie population but no attempt to sample the population has ever been made. Our goal in the spring of 2014 was to investigate likely Muskie spawning areas and determine the potential for setting nets in those areas in the future. An electrofishing boat was used to investigate the areas so that if any Muskies were encountered, we could attempt to capture them. The electrofishing boat provided addtitional information regarding the potential for by-catch (suckers, Yellow Perch, etc.) if we decide to attempt a netting assessment in the future. During the late spring of 2014, spring water temperatures were quite cold for the first 10 days after ice-out but than a stretch of uncommonly long and hot weather resulted in the water temperatures rising rapidly and remaining warm.

After investigating four areas of Winnie and Cut Foot Sioux, we continue to suspect the Muskie population is low in Winnie and connected waters. In addition to us not having a great feeling for the available spring Muskie habitat, the spring conditions in 2014 likely hindered our ability to encounter more fish. Many challenges to sampling Muskies were identified during this initial investigation (e.g. large areas of wild rice). A total of four Muskies were encountered and this number likely does not reflect the population. However, it is probable that a future assessment with our improved knowledge of the habitat, an increase in effort, addition of some trap netting, and improved spring conditions would still result in a relatively low number Muskies being sampled. Although improved size structure and distribution would be described, and additional fish for genetic samples collected for ancestry, we would still conclude the population was generally low.

This special assessment contains data from 8 mid-lake gill net sets that were first set in 1997. These nets were initially set to determine if catch rate and growth statistics for various fish species were similar to those of the 24 near-shore gill net sets and were set in conjunction with the 24 near-shore sets. After many years of sampling it appears that catch rate and size distribution can vary between the two net groups for Walleye, Northern Pike, and Yellow Perch while growth of fish appears to be similar.

Walleye; Walleye catch rates varied similarly to near-shore nets from 1997 to 2006, then appeared to move independently between 2006 and 2013. Gill net catch rates in near-shore and mid-lake gill nets were similar in 2014 and 2015. Walleye were sampled at a rate of 4.1 per net in 2015. Mid-lake sampled Walleye varied from 11.6 to 23.0 inches with a mean length of 18.6 inches. Gill net catch of the 2012 year class for near-shore gill nets was also low. The 2012 year class continues to be one of the weakest observed since the beginning of the Large Lake Program (1983).

The catch per gill net of Walleye longer than 19 inches has been used as an indicator of quality for the Walleye population. The mean catch of Walleye longer than 19 inches sampled per mid-lake net since 1999 was 1.19 per net. This catch rate was similar to the mean catch of 1.22 Walleye longer than 19 inches per near-shore gill net set since 2000. The catch rate of Walleye longer than 19 inches was 2.38 per mid-lake net in 2015.

Northern Pike; Mid-lake gill net catches of Northern Pike (pike) are typically less than near-shore nets and 2015 was no different. The mid-lake catch of pike per net decreased from 6.0 per net in 2014 to 4.3 per net in 2015. Pike sampled in 2015 varied from 17.1 to 25.8 inches with a mean length of 20.9 inches.

Yellow Perch; Yellow Perch (perch) sampled in mid-lake nets have typically been sampled at a higher rate than from near shore nets. Results of the 2015 assessment followed that trend, with a catch rate of 55.3 per mid-lake net compared to 43.1 per near-shore net. The mean catch per gill net since 1997 has been higher in mid-lake gill nets (81.6) than near-shore gill nets (72.2). Although catch rates have been higher in mid-lake nets, the catch per gill net lift has varied similarly between near-shore and mid-lake gill nets. Perch sampled in mid-lake nets varied from 4.5 to 11.9 inches with a mean length of 6.9 inches.

Relative health of the perch population has been described by the percent of perch longer than nine inches in the gill net catch. The catch of perch longer than 9 inches (large perch) in near-shore gill nets declined to 6% in the early 1990's driven by high angler harvest. Changes in Lake Winnibigoshish and other lakes prompted a statewide change in the Yellow Perch bag limit to 20 daily and 40 in possession in 2001. Strong year classes were produced in 1994 and 1997 which resulted in high catch rates of large perch in the early 2000's. The catch of large perch started to decline in 2004 and has declined from 45.9% in 2004 to near 16% in 2010 and 2011. The percent of perch longer than 9 inches increased to 11.5% in 2015 from 10.5% in 2014.

Thirty two gill nets were set during the last two weeks of September, 2015. This was the ninth consecutive year of fall sampling. The goals of this netting are: 1) develop a population estimate of adult Walleye using available population models, 2) determine accurate sex ratios and spawning stock biomass for the Lake Winnibigoshish Walleye population, and 3) build on the long term data set of fall netting so that fall netting may eventually replace summer netting as the annual index of abundance for primary fish species in Lake Winnibigoshish.

The gill net catch of 7.7 Walleye per net in 2015 increased by 20% from the catch of 6.4 per net in 2014. Developing a similar annual index of abundance has been difficult. Summer and fall mean gill net catch rates resulted in opposite trends between 2007 and 2011, making comparisons between the two challenging. Since that time, summer and fall gill net catch rates have resulted in similar trends, although much variability was still evident. It is likely that more time will be required to develop an comparable annual index. Size structure was good, with fish present from 7.5 to 25.3 inches. With the exception of age 11, all ages of Walleye between 0 and 15 were represented. An index of year class strength was computed for the 2008 through 2013 year classes. The 2009, 2010, 2011 and 2013 year classes were average, and the 2008 and 2012 year classes were weak.

Yellow Perch (perch) catch rates varied from 17.5 to 38.5 between 2007 and 2013. The catch rate of 17.3 per net in 2014 was a new low, and was followed by a historic high catch rate of 43.1 per net in 2015. The difference in catch rates was primarily due to high catch rates of the 2012 year class. Perch varied from 4.5 to 12.2 inches with a mean length of 7.1 inches. Age classes 2 through 10 perch were sampled, however, the 2012 year class made up 59% of the catch. The proportion of perch longer than 9 inches has varied between 16 and 18 percent between 2011 and 2014. The percent of perch longer than 9 inches decreased to 12.4 percent in 2015, primarily due to the abundant 2012 year class that were less than 7 inches in length. Fall gill net catch rates continue to be lower than summer catch rates, and the percent of perch longer than 9 inches continues to be higher than summer near shore netting. Neither of these appeared to be explained by growth of perch between summer and fall survey dates.

Northern Pike (pike) were sampled at a rate of 5.8 per gill net in 2015. This catch rate was the second consecutive historic high (range 3.0-5.8, mean 4.1). Pike length varied from 10.6 to 37.3 inches with a mean length of 22.8 inches. Pike age structure varied similarly to the summer assessment with ages one through seven represented. As with most Lake Winnibigoshish assessments, the majority of pike sampled were from the age two, three, and four cohorts.

The gill net catch of Cisco increased to 8.8 in 2015 from the historic low of 2.8 in 2014. Although the catch rate increased, the catch of 8.8 per net remains below the third quartile. Low catch rates of Cisco were expected in 2013 due to a summer kill during the summer of 2012. The continued low catch in 2015 was not expected, however, the increased catch may indicate that Cisco are recovering. Cisco length varied from 5.0 to 15.7 inches with a mean length of 12.0 inches.

The Walleye population on Lake Winnibigoshish (Winnie) has seen its ups and downs over time. Presently, we are in a down period. Walleye reproduction and recruitment to the fishery was generally good between 2001 and 2011, with numerous strong year classes and increasing catch rates in DNR assessment nets. Since 2012 Winnie Walleye have seen below average recruitment, with only one strong year class produced (2013) and likely four weak year classes. Full evaluation of the 2016 and 2017 year classes is not complete, so evaluation of those year classes may change. Below average recruitment since 2012 has resulted in less small Walleye present in the system, which may result in anglers catching fewer keeper size fish.

Although less small Walleye are currently in the lake, the 2015 year class appears to be average, and those fish should be 14 to 16 inches in length during the summer of 2018. Walleye from the strong 2013 and earlier year classes are still abundant in the lake which should result in good catches of fish longer than 18 inches. The larger Walleye are mostly mature fish that have the potential to produce a strong year class when conditions are right.

Clear water continues to drive Walleye fishing success. Walleye have large, light sensitive eyes and prefer to feed in low visibility conditions. Due to this, fishing in the early morning, evening, or on windy days should result in better success.

Northern Pike continue to be abundant in Winnie, and they are easily caught during mid-day! The population of pike has been increasing since the mid 1990's. As the pike population expanded, the average size and number of pike longer than 30 inches decreased. Although the pike population remains near the historic high, the average size has been increasing over the past several years and is now the largest since 2001. The number of pike longer than 30 inches sampled is still relatively low. However, with the 22 to 26 inch protected slot limit that will be in effect for north central MN lakes starting in 2018, the number of quality sized pike should increase. Pike prey heavily on Yellow Perch and Cisco. High numbers of pike can have a negative effect on those populations. The new pike regulation should help reduce the overly abundant pike population, reduce pressure on the perch population, and result in larger average size for pike.

Yellow Perch are an important species for anglers and as a prey item for pike, Walleye, and perch. Perch abundance and the percent of quality perch has varied over time. Perch were extremely abundant with many quality perch in the 1980's. As perch became more popular as a game fish, a booming perch fishery was created on Winnie. The increased harvest of perch caused a decline in average size and the number of quality size perch in the lake. The current limit of 20 daily and 40 in possession was implemented in 2001. Over time the perch population stabilized at a level that is less than the 1980's, but much higher than most lakes. Although anglers remove many large perch from Winnie each year, the increase in predators (both pike and Walleye) likely play a large role in observed changes to the perch population.

The 2017 assessment saw average catch rates of perch, an increasing number of perch longer than 9 inches, and good size structure. Gill net catch rates were similar between 2016 and 2017. Relative quality of the perch population is described by the percent of perch longer than 9 inches. The percent of perch longer than 9 inches increased to 15.6% in 2017 from 8.3% in 2016. Gill net sampled perch length varied from 4.6 to 12.1 inches and age 3 to 9.

Cisco (also known as tullibee or herring) are an important prey item for large Walleye and Northern Pike, and were caught in low numbers in 2017. There was a substantial summer kill observed during the summer of 2012. Catch rates typically recover two to three years following a summer kill as the remaining adults have better success spawning, and their off-spring have less competition from older fish and tend to do well. The Cisco population has not recovered as of the summer of 2017.

Lake Winnibigoshish and the Cut Foot Sioux Lakes also provide opportunities to fish for other species. Black Crappie, sunfish and bass are found in the big lake, but more so in Cut Foot Sioux. The lakes also provide an opportunity to catch a muskie. Few anglers actually target muskies but some are caught while fishing for other fish.

Winnie and connected waters contain faucet snails, and zebra mussels have been sampled annually since 2012. Adult zebra mussel were found for the first time in 2016 and covered nearly all hard surfaces in 2017. With the discovery of zebra mussels it is important that all boaters do a thorough job draining and cleaning their equipment. If you are going to fish a couple of lakes in the same day, make Winnie the last stop so you don't inadvertently spread invasive species to other waters.

Starry stonewort (a non-native algae that looks similar to chara) was discovered in 2016. By the fall of 2017 it had spread from the Third River in the northwest corner of the lake south and east to the Mississippi River outlet in the northeast corner of the lake. This plant spreads through fragmentation, so it is important to check equipment and remove all plant fragments.

Please feel free to contact the DNR Area Fisheries Office in Grand Rapids at (218) 328-8836 or by e-mail at grandrapids.fisheries@state.mn.us if you have any questions.

Lake Winnibigoshish is part of the Mississippi River headwaters reservoir system and is located 15 miles northwest of Deer River. The lake is a large, shallow, wind-swept reservoir with a sandy shoreline and gently sloping shoal areas. Winnibigoshish has a surface area of 56,544 acres, mean depth of 15.1 feet, and a maximum depth of 70 feet. Water clarity was high in 2022 and Secchi depths ranged from 11 to 23 feet.

Lake Winnibigoshish has been managed as part of the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources large lake program since 1983. Management activities include special fishing regulations, Walleye fry stocking, occasional creel surveys, and annual fish surveys. Walleye harvest has been regulated with a special regulation since 2000. The regulation was relaxed to a 6 fish limit with a 18 to 23-inch protective slot limit in 2015 to allow some additional harvest of larger fish which were common at the time. Winnibigoshish lies within the North-central Pike Zone, which was established in 2018. Lakes within this zone are regulated with a 22 to 26-inch PSL with a bag limit of 10 fish but only two can be longer than 26 inches. Spearing has an exception of one fish in the PSL.

Winnibigoshish is considered a premier Walleye destination and substantial effort is directed towards Walleye management. Fall gill net catches have varied due to fluctuations in year-class strength. The 2022 catch was below average for Winnibigoshish but within the typical range for lakes with similar habitats. The lower catch rate was largely driven by a decline in fish over 18 inches. The decreased number of larger individuals was not unexpected. Multiple below average year-classes were produced between 2014 and 2017 thus limiting the number of fish recruiting to larger sizes. Stronger year-classes were produced in 2018 and 2019 which contributed to a shift in size and age distributions favoring smaller individuals. Age distribution was heavily influenced by the strong 2019 year-class. The size distribution was favorable for anglers and featured good harvest opportunities. Walleye within the 18 to 23-inch protected slot comprised 7.4% of the sample. This compares to over 70% in 2017 and 2018 when the population was dominated by large individuals and few harvestable fish were available. Growth was typical for Minnesota lakes with Walleye averaging 14.8 inches by age-4. Walleye averaged almost 15 inches in 2022 and fish up to 25 inches were sampled. Thirty-two percent of the sampled Walleye exceeded 15 inches.

Winnibigoshish provides a destination Yellow Perch fishery with a history of producing fish over ten inches. Yellow Perch is also an important prey species. Catch rates have varied but have declined following a 2016 peak and were lower than expected in the last four surveys. The 2022 catch rate was the lowest observed and low compared to similar lakes. Fisheries surveys have documented declines in perch catch rates across Minnesota since the 1970s but contributing factors are not well understood. Contributing elements on Winnibigoshish may include a combination of factors such as recent predation by strong Walleye year-classes, a prolonged decline in Cisco as an alternate prey item, ecosystem changes related to Zebra Mussel infestation and climate, and a prolonged period of reduced recruitment to larger sizes. All sizes of perch were sampled in relatively low numbers in 2022, but perch under 9 inches showed the greatest decline suggesting poor recruitment in the recent past. Growth resembled past surveys and was near the statewide average with fish typically reaching 8 inches by age-5. Despite low numbers, perch size distribution remained favorable for anglers and the presence of larger perch suggested modest angling opportunities. Perch averaged 8.2 inches and fish over 11 inches were sampled. Thirteen percent of the sampled perch exceeded 10 inches.

Northern Pike is another popular species and well suited for Winnibigoshish and connected waters. Winnibigoshish often had higher pike catch rates than comparable lakes, largely due to an abundance of preferred spawning habitats. The 2022 catch was low compared to previous surveys, but resembled pike catches on other large lakes. Lower pike numbers are often desirable because they are associated with faster growth and better size quality. The 2022 length distribution was modest and resembled previous fall surveys. Pike averaged 21.8 inches and fish over 32 inches were sampled. Only 5% of the pike exceeded 28 inches. The Winnibigoshish population has been dominated by 2- to 5-year-old pike and older fish have been rare. The 2022 age distribution resembled past surveys as ages ranged from one to six. Growth was similar to past surveys and relatively fast with pike averaging 24.8 inches by age-4. Protected slot sized fish comprised around 40% of the sample since 2018. In 2022, 38% of the catch was within the PSL. Anglers and spearers are encouraged to focus harvest on fish under 22 inches while releasing or passing on larger fish to help improve size quality.

Cisco are an important prey species and an indicator species due to their environmental sensitivity. Catches have declined over the past decade following a 2012 summer kill event. The 2022 catch was the lowest observed. Warmer water temperatures and Zebra Mussel infestations are two factors that have likely influenced poor Cisco numbers.

Invasive exotic species are not native to Minnesota and cause economic or environmental harm or harm to human health. They are illegal to introduce into or move between state waters and can impact energy flow, food chains, and fish species assemblages. Several species have been introduced into Lake Winnibigoshish including Zebra Mussels, Faucet and Mystery Snails, and Starry Stonewort. Changing environmental conditions resulting from these introductions caused changes in gamefish habitat and habits, which likely impact fish sampling and anglers. Gill net catches have likely been influenced by these changes, especially since the establishment of Zebra Mussels in 2012. Zebra Mussels are an efficient filter feeder that have been shown to impact energy transfer and aquatic food webs. The median biomass of fish sampled in gill nets declined since 2016 suggesting a decrease in overall carrying capacity for fish following Zebra Mussel establishment. Each of these introductions have occurred through human activities. Movement of any type of equipment that can trap or hold contaminated water, plant fragments or aquatic organisms can be a potential vector of spread if precautions are not taken. To avoid being an accomplice to the spread of these unwanted species, people should ensure that all equipment is thoroughly cleaned and dried before moving it to a new body of water. More information is available at https://www.dnr.state.mn.us/invasives/ais/index.html.

Gillnet catch rates for walleye decreased from 7.3 per net in 1997 to 5.6 per net in 1998, and to 3.6 per net in 1999. The 1999 catch rate was less than the mean catch of 4.6 per net observed since 1983. The 1994 and 1995 year classes were considered strong in 1998, however, assessment data for 1999 indicates that the 1994 year class is still strong while the 1995 year class is now considered average. Anecdotal information suggests that high fishing pressure and a corresponding high harvest of the 1994 and 1995 year-classes of walleye was seen during the 1998 and 1999 summer angling seasons. The rapid decline in gill net catch rate with 2 strong year classes present may indicate that walleye were being harvested at a rate that is not sustainable.

Irregular recruitment which occurred between 1985 and 1994 resulted in one average year class (1991) and all others below average or week. This most likely resulted in the majority of harvested walleye during the 1997, 1998, and 1999 fishing seasons being from the 1994 and 1995 year classes. As intense fishing pressure was exerted on the fishery, walleye abundance may have been reduced to a point that approaches levels observed prior to the 1994 and 1995 year classes recruitment to the fishery. Recruitment for the 1996 and 1998 year classes appears to be average while 1997 is poor. The mean length and weight for gill net captured walleye at 14.9 inches and 1.3 pounds in 1999 was similar to 1998 and the long term mean.

The gill net catch rate for yellow perch of 90.4 per assessment net in 1999 was similar to both 1998 and historic mean catch per net values. The proportion of perch greater than 9 inches at 13.2% in 1999 was identical to 1998, however the number of perch > 9 inches per net decreased from 14.3 per net in 1998 to 11.9 per net in 1999. The 1994 and 1997 year classes of perch appear to be strong with indices of year-class strength of 207 and 181 respectively. The majority of the 1994 year class have reached angler preferred sizes and likely made a large contribution to angler harvest during the 1999-2000 winter season. The 1993 year-class is of average abundance and has attained angler preferred sizes. All other year-classes sampled had below average indices of year-class-strength, however, none would be considered weak.

Northern pike mean catch per gill net decreased to 7.1 per net in 1999 from 9.1 per net in 1998. Size structures for the northern pike population remained similar to all years sampled since 1983. The mean length and weight for northern pike of 22.9 inches and 3.3 pounds, respectively in 1999 increased slightly from 1998 levels.

Stomach contents of northern pike were examined for the sixth consecutive year. Over those six years the population of prey species has varied by year. During this time frame cisco and yellow perch have been the most important components in the northern pike diet. However, cisco continue to be the most common species that northern pike consume. It appears that pike select cisco over other prey species during the warm water period, regardless of the availability of other prey species.

Walleye abundance decreased from the second highest observed in 1997 to below average in 1999. Walleye abundance rebounded to above average in 2000 due to the resilience of the 1994 and 1995 year classes and a strong 1998 year class. The Lake Winnibigoshish walleye fishery appears to be more robust than it has been since the late 1980s. Two strong year classes (1998 and 1994) and two average year classes (1995 and 1996) dominated the walleye population. Preliminary gill net and trawl data indicate that the 1999 year class may also be of above average abundance.

A 17 to 26 inch protected slot limit was enacted in 2000. This resulted in the release of most walleye older than the 1995 year class, and may also have contributed to higher abundance indices. The 1998 year class of walleye experienced fast growth in 1998 and 1999. As a result, the average 2+ year old (1998 year class) walleye was nearly two inches larger than expected. The additional growth may also have resulted in higher abundance indices. Young of the year walleye were captured by trawl at near all time low rates in 2000. These walleye also experienced slow growth during their first summer and may ultimately be a weak year class. The mean length and weight for gill net captured walleye at 15.3 inches and 1.4 pounds in 2000 was similar to the long term mean.

The gill net catch rate for yellow perch of 92.6 per assessment net was similar to both 1999 and historic mean catch rates. The proportion of perch greater than 9 inches at 20.0% was 50% higher than in 1999, and the number of perch > 9 inches per net increased from 11.9 per net in 1999 to 18.5 per net in 2000. The majority of this increase was due to the strong 1994 year class growing to sizes exceeding 9 inches. As with the 1998 year class of walleye, the 1994 year class of yellow perch has experienced fast growth. This fast growth resulted in perch recruiting to the 9+ inch size faster which may also have resulted in greater numbers of 9+ inch perch. The 1994 year class appears to be strong with an index of year-class strength of 192. The majority of the 1994 year class has reached angler preferred sizes and likely made a large contribution to angler harvest during the 2000-2001 winter angling harvest. The 1995 and 1997 year class were of average abundance. Most individuals from those two year classes have attained angler preferred sizes. All other year classes sampled had below average indices of year- class strength, however, none would be considered weak.

Northern pike relative abundance increased to 8.2 per net in 2000 from 7.1 per net in 1999. Size structures for the northern pike population remained similar to all years sampled since 1983. The mean length and weight for northern pike of 22.8 inches and 3.1 pounds in 2000 was nearly identical to long term averages.

Stomach contents were examined for all gill net captured northern pike for the seventh consecutive year. Over those seven years the population of prey species has varied by year. During this time frame cisco and yellow perch have been the most important components in the northern pike diet. However, cisco continue to be the most common species that northern pike consume. It appears that pike select cisco over other prey species during the warm water period, regardless of the availability of other prey species.

Walleye were captured at a rate of 6.7 per net, which was higher than typical for Lake Winnibigoshish. Walleye sampled varied from 6.7 to 27.4 inches with a mean length of 15.9 inches and mean weight of 1.6 pounds. The walleye population appeared to be healthy with all age classes sampled between age 1 and 10. Year-class strength was computed for walleye between age 2 and 7. Two weak year classes, three average year classes, and the strong 2001year class were sampled. The 1994 and 1995 year classes were also well represented, and contributed to the above average catch of 19 to 25 inch walleye. Relatively few age-1 walleye were captured by gill net indicating that the 2004 year class will likely be weak. Mean back-calculated growth was similar to the Lake Winnibigoshish average for most ages, attaining 15.7 inches after four growing seasons. The mean total weight of walleye per gill net of 10.9 pounds exceeded the third quartile for Lake Winnibigoshish, and was similar to the Lake-class 26 median.

Cold spring and early summer conditions may have caused lower hatch rates of walleye eggs with slower initial growth and higher mortality of walleye fry and fingerlings. Rapid warming in mid June appears to have resulted in good growth for age-o walleye that survived the inhospitable spring conditions.

Yellow perch were sampled at a historic low rate of 47.6 per near-shore gill net. Perch sampled in 2005 varied from 4.6 to 12.2 inches with a mean length of 7.4 inches. Catch rates and size structure of sampled perch have changed recently. Catch rates started a slow decline in the late 1990s, but were within historic norms until 2003. Catch rates from 2003 through 2005 were below the first quartile for Lake Winnibigoshish. Although recent catch rates have been low for Lake Winnibigoshish they were well within norms for lakes of this type.

Age classes 2 through 7, 9, and 10 were sampled by gill net. Year class strength was computed for ages 3 through 7. The 1998, 1999, and 2001 year classes were average, while the 2000 and 2002 year classes were considered weak. Catch rates of age-6 through age 10-perch were much lower than that of ages 3 through 5, and were a relatively small component of the total catch. Yellow perch growth was relatively slow through age 2, increased to near average from age 3 to age 10, with perch attaining a mean length of 9.2 inches at age 6.

Relative health of the yellow perch population has been described by the percent of perch longer than 9 inches in the gill net catch. As perch catch rates decreased the proportion of large perch (longer than 9 inches) increased. The proportion of large perch peaked as gill net catch rates fell below the first quartile. In 2005, the proportion of large perch sampled in near-shore gill nets declined for the first time since 1998. Seventeen percent of near-shore gill net sampled perch exceeded 9 inches.

The microsporidian parasite heterosporis has been documented in Lake Winnibigoshish yellow perch. Of 1,143 perch sampled in 2005 no evidence of heterosporis was observed.

Northern pike were sampled at a historic high rate of 11.5 per near-shore gill net. Catch rates have increased since 1999 and have exceeded the third quartile in three of the last four years. Pike sampled in near-shore gill nets varied from 12.8 to 32.2 inches with a mean length of 20.9 inches. All age classes between age 1 and 7 were sampled by gill net. Age-2 and age-3 pike were the most abundant age classes sampled.

Gill net catch rates of cisco rebounded to average levels for both near-shore and mid-lake nets in 2005. The catch rate of 25.0 per near-shore net was similar to the long-term average. Bony structures were not collected from cisco in 2005 and ages were not determined. Examination of the cisco length frequency indicates that the population was dominated by two year-classes of young fish with few cisco exceeding 12 inches.

The Walleye population on Lake Winnibigoshish (Winnie) has seen its ups and downs over time. Presently, we are in a down period. Walleye reproduction and recruitment to the fishery was generally good between 2001 and 2011, with numerous strong year classes and increasing catch rates in DNR assessment nets. Since 2012 Winnie Walleye have seen below average recruitment, with only one strong year class produced (2013) and likely four weak year classes. I say likely, since full evaluation of the 2016 and 2017 year classes is not complete. Below average recruitment since 2012 has resulted in less small Walleye present in the system, which may result in anglers catching fewer keeper size fish.

Although less small Walleye are currently in the lake, the 2015 year class appears to be average, and those fish should be 14 to 16 inches in length during the summer of 2018. Walleye from the strong 2013 and earlier year classes are still abundant in the lake which should result in good catches of fish longer than 18 inches. The larger Walleye are mostly mature fish that have the potential to produce a strong year class when conditions are right.

Clear water continues to drive Walleye fishing success. Walleye have large, light sensitive eyes and prefer to feed in low visibility conditions. Due to this, fishing in the early morning, evening, or on windy days should result in better success.

Northern Pike continue to be abundant in Winnie, and they are easily caught during mid-day! The population of pike has been increasing since the mid 1990's. As the pike population expanded, the average size and number of pike longer than 30 inches decreased. Although the pike population remains near the historic high, the average size has been increasing over the past several years and is now the largest since 2001. The number of pike longer than 30 inches sampled is still relatively low. However, with the 22 to 26 inch protected slot limit that will be in effect for north central MN lakes starting in 2018, the number of quality sized pike should increase. Pike prey heavily on Yellow Perch and Cisco. High numbers of pike can have a negative effect on those populations. The new pike regulation should help reduce the overly abundant pike population, reduce pressure on the perch population, and result in larger average size for pike.

Yellow Perch are an important species for both anglers and as a prey item for pike, Walleye, and perch. Perch abundance and the percent of quality perch has varied over time. Perch were extremely abundant with many quality perch in the 1980's. As perch became more popular as a game fish, a booming perch fishery was created on Winnie. The increased harvest of perch caused a decline in average size and the number of quality size perch in the lake. The current limit of 20 daily and 40 in possession was implemented in 2001. Over time the perch population stabilized at a level that is less than the 1980's, but much higher than most lakes. Although anglers remove many large perch from Winnie each year, the increase in predators (both pike and Walleye) likely play a large role in observed changes to the perch population.

The 2017 assessment saw average catch rates of perch, an increasing number of perch longer than 9 inches, and good size structure. Gill net catch rates were similar between 2016 and 2017. Relative quality of the perch population is described by the percent of perch longer than 9 inches. The percent of perch longer than 9 inches increased to 15.6% in 2017 from 8.3% in 2016. Gill net sampled perch length varied from 4.6 to 12.1 inches and age 3 to 9.

Cisco: Cisco (also known as tullibee or herring) are an important prey item for large Walleye and Northern Pike, and were caught in low numbers in 2017. There was a substantial summer kill observed during the summer of 2012. Catch rates typically recover two to three years following a summer kill as the remaining adults have better success spawning, and their off-spring have less competition from older fish and tend to do well. The cisco population has not recovered as of the summer of 2017.

Lake Winnibigoshish and the Cut Foot Sioux Lakes also provide opportunities to fish for other species. Black Crappie, sunfish and bass are found in the big lake, but more so in Cut Foot Sioux. The lakes also provide an opportunity to catch a muskie. Few anglers actually target muskies but some are caught while fishing for other fish.

Winnie and connected waters contain faucet snails, and zebra mussels have been sampled annually since 2012. Adult zebra mussel were found for the first time in 2016 and covered nearly all hard surfaces in 2017. With the discovery of zebra mussels it is important that all boaters do a thorough job draining and cleaning their equipment. If you are going to fish a couple of lakes in the same day, make Winnie the last stop so you don't inadvertently spread invasive species to other waters.

Starry stonewort (a non-native algae that looks similar to chara) was discovered in 2016. By the fall of 2017 it had spread from the Third River in the northwest corner of the lake south and east to the Mississippi River outlet in the northeast corner of the lake. This plant spreads through fragmentation, so it is important to check equipment and remove all plant fragments.

Please feel free to contact the DNR Area Fisheries Office in Grand Rapids at (218) 328-8837 or by email at grandrapds.fisheries@state.mn.us if you have any questions.

The lake Winnibigoshish assessment is completed annually to track changes in abundance and growth of all game species. The assessment season starts with gill netting in late June. Gill netting is conducted through July to sample game and non-game species age 1 and older. Abundance, growth rates, presence of parasites etc. is determined from this data. Seining is conducted during the month of July. The goal of seining is to sample young game and non-game species (including minnows) and to track growth of age 0 walleye and perch. Trawling is conducted in August to continue tracking growth rates of age-0 walleye and perch. Trawling gives us the first clue to abundance of age-0 walleye and perch for that year. Temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles are taken from June through August and water chemistry analysis is done in August to track changes in the system that may affect the ability of some species to prosper or exist in the lake.

Walleye
Gill nets
Walleye were sampled at a rate of 5.0 per net, which was average for Lake Winnibigoshish. Walleye sampled varied from 7.1 to 25.2 inches with a mean length of 15.2 inches and mean weight of 1.4 pounds. The walleye population appeared to be healthy with most age classes sampled between age 1 and 12. Year-class strength was computed for walleye between age 2 and 7. Three average year classes (2003, 2004 and 2005), and three strong year classes (2001, 2002, and 2006) were sampled. However, none of the strong year classes were exceptionally strong. Mean back-calculated growth was similar to the Lake Winnibigoshish and statewide average for all ages, attaining 17.9 inches after five growing seasons.

Seine and trawl
Slow spring warming and below average summer temperatures appear to have resulted in some of the slowest growth observed since 1983. The shortened growing season resulted in smaller than average age-0 walleye. Slow growth and small size of fingerling walleye usually results in a weak year class.

Relatively few age-0 walleye were sampled by seine in 2008. Seine catch rates have not correlated to ultimate year-class strength for walleye in Lake Winnibigoshish. Growth rate of age-0 walleye has been a better predictor of year-class strength. Mean lengths of age-0 walleye varied from 2.5 inches to 3.2 inches from July 18 to July 31.

Mean trawl catch rates for age-0 walleye were average when compared to catch rates observed since 1972. Age-0 walleye growth recorded through the first week of August was slower than mean growth in all but three years since 1983, reaching a mean length of 3.8 inches on August 8. Slow growth of age 0 walleye nearly always results in a weak year class.

Yellow perch
Gill nets
Yellow perch (perch) are an important species for anglers and as a prey item for walleye and northern pike. The catch of perch in assessment nets reached an all-time low in 2005 largely because of poor year classes in 2000 and 2002. A strong year class was produced in 2003. As this year class has matured, the catch of perch has increased.

Perch were captured at a rate of 68.4 per net in 2008. This catch rate was slightly lower than average for lake Winnibigoshish. Perch sampled in 2008 varied from 4.8 to 11.2 inches with a mean length of 7.3 inches and mean weight of 0.19 pounds. Age classes 2 through 8 were sampled by gill net. An index of year-class strength was computed for ages 3 through 7. The 2001 and 2004 year classes were average, the 2002 year class was weak, and the 2003 and 2005 year classes were strong. As the 2003 and 2005 year classes continue to mature, abundance and size structure should continue to improve. The catch was biased towards younger perch with 69% of the catch made up of age 2 through age 4 fish. Yellow perch growth was relatively slow through age 2, then increased to average from age 3 to age 10. Perch grew to a mean length of 9.3 inches at age 6.

Relative health of the yellow perch population has been described by the percent of perch longer than 9 inches in the gill net catch. As perch catch rates decreased during the mid 1990's, the proportion of large perch (longer than 9 inches) increased. The proportion of large perch peaked as gill net catch rates fell below the first quartile. In 2005, the proportion of large perch sampled in gill nets declined for the first time since 1998. The proportion of perch longer than nine inches was stable in 2005 and 2006 at 16.9 percent, then declined to 9.8% as young perch were recruited to the fishery in 2007. Although many small fish remain in the population, the strong 2003 year class has grown large enough to affect the proportion of perch longer than 9 inches. The proportion of perch longer than 9 inches increased to 12.7 percent in 2008.

The microsporidian parasite heterosporis has been documented in Lake Winnibigoshish yellow perch. No evidence of heterosporis was observed 2008.

Seine and trawl
Catch rates of age-0 yellow perch were near average for both seine and trawl. No correlation is evident between catch rates of age-0 yellow perch and ultimate year-class strength.

Northern pike

Gill net catch rates of northern pike (pike) increased from 1999 through 2005 and exceeded the third quartile in four of six years from 2002 through 2007. Northern pike catch rates declined to 8.2 per gill net in 2008. Pike sampled varied from 14.8 to 29.7 inches with a mean length of 21.4 inches. All age classes between age 1 and 6, and age 8 were sampled by gill net. Age two, three, and four pike were most abundant, and pike exhibited growth rates that were similar to state wide averages through all ages.

No pike longer than 30 inches were sampled in this assessment. This does not mean that they are not present in the system, but it is an indication that their abundance has decreased. The decrease in size structure can be attributed to several causes. Cisco abundance has declined (cisco are preferred prey that provides more energy than other similar size prey), this may lead to slower growth rates. Conditions for reproduction and survival have been good. This may lead to increased density and more competition for food, which also causes decreased growth rates. Angler harvest can have a large impact on the size structure of a pike population. When anglers harvest the largest fish they catch, they can cause a slow decrease in the size structure of the fish they are harvesting. This occurs because fish are removed faster than they can be replaced. Considering the current size structure anglers should release all pike longer than 25 inches. This should result in pike growing closer to their potential and increase the chance to catch 8 to 10 pound fish.

Cisco
Gill net catch rates decreased to the third lowest level observed since 1983. The catch rate of 10.5 per net was well below the first quartile. The cisco population has been lower than average for 8 of the last 10 years. This is likely due to increasing water temperatures affecting reproduction and survival. Cisco sampled in 2008 varied from 5.4 to 15.4 inches with a mean length of 8.2 inches.

Water Quality
Water samples were taken on August 5, 2008. Physical and chemical parameters measured were within the range observed since 1983. Six temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken between June 23 and August 8, 2008. Dissolved oxygen stratification was evident from July 21, through August 5. No evidence of thermal stratification was found in 2008. Thermal and dissolved oxygen stratification may result during periods of high air temperatures and low wind. When wind speeds increase to moderate levels (15 mph) the entire water column appears to mix.

Walleye were sampled at a rate of 6.4 per net, which was higher than typical for Lake Winnibigoshish. Walleye sampled varied from 7.3 to 25.1 inches with a mean length of 14.3 inches and mean weight of 1.2 pounds. The walleye population appeared to be healthy with all age classes sampled between age 1 and 10. Year-class strength was computed for walleye between age 2 and 7. Two weak year classes (1999 and 2000), two average year classes (2003 and 2004), and two strong year class (2001 and 2002) were sampled. Walleye catch rates were higher than average for most length groups in 2006. The high catch of 7, 8, and 9 inch walleye (age-one) may indicate that the 2005 year class will be strong. Mean back-calculated growth was similar to the Lake Winnibigoshish average for most ages, attaining 17.9 inches after five growing seasons.

Rapid spring warming and above average summer temperatures appear to have resulted in fast growth and large size of age-0 walleye. Fast growth and large size of fingerling walleye typically results in a strong year class.

Relatively few age-0 walleye were sampled by seine in 2006. Seine catch rates have not correlated to ultimate year-class strength for Lake Winnibigoshish. Growth rates of age-1 walleye have been a better predictor of year-class strength. Growth of seine captured age-1 walleye was fast compared to historic norms. Mean lengths of age-0 walleye varied from 3.2 inches to 4.6 inches from July 4 to July 25.

Trawling was done during the first two weeks of August. Mean trawl catch rates for age-0, 1, and 2 walleye were similar to historic means. Age-0 walleye growth recorded through the first two weeks of August was fast when compared with annual assessments since 1983 with a mean length of 5.1 inches. Average catch rates combined with fast growth typically results in above average to strong year-class strength.

Yellow perch were captured at a rate of 56.6 per net, which was lower than typical for Lake Winnibigoshish. Perch sampled in 2006 varied from 5.0 to 11.8 inches with a mean length of 7.3 inches. Catch rates and size structure of sampled perch have changed recently. Catch rates started a slow decline in the late 1990s, but were within historic norms until 2003. Catch rates from 2003 through 2006 were below the first quartile for Lake Winnibigoshish. Although recent catch rates have been low, they were well within norms when compared to similar lakes.

Age classes 2 through 9 were sampled by gill net. Year-class strength was computed for ages 3 through 8. The 1998, 1999, and 2001year classes were average, the 2000 and 2002 year classes were weak, and the 2003 year class was strong. Catch rates of age-6 through age-9 perch were much lower than that of ages 3 through 5, and were a relatively small component of the total catch. Yellow perch growth was relatively slow through age 2, increased to near average from age 3 to age 10, with perch attaining a mean length of 9.5 inches at age 6.

Relative health of the yellow perch population has been described by the percent of perch longer than 9 inches in the gill net catch. As perch catch rates decreased the proportion of perch longer than 9 inches increased. The proportion of large perch peaked as gill net catch rates fell below the first quartile. In 2005, the proportion of large perch sampled in near-shore gill nets declined for the first time since 1998. The proportion of perch longer than nine inches was stable in 2005 and 2006 at 16.9 percent.

The microsporidian parasite heterosporis has been documented in Lake Winnibigoshish yellow perch. Of 140 of perch sampled in 2006 no evidence of heterosporis was observed.

Catch rates of northern pike increased from 1999 through 2005 and exceeded the third quartile in three of five years since 2002. Northern pike catch rates decreased to a near average rate of 8.6 per near-shore gill net in 2006. Pike sampled in near-shore gill nets varied from 15.2 to 36.5 inches with a mean length of 21.7 inches. All age classes between age 1 and 7 were sampled by gill net. Age-2 and age-3 pike were the most abundant age classes sampled.

The catch rate of 19.3 cisco per near-shore net was near the first quartile. Cisco sampled in near-shore gill nets varied from 6.9 to 17.1 inches with a mean length of 9.5 inches. Bony structures were not collected from cisco in 2006 and ages were not determined. Examination of the length frequency indicates that three year classes may have been sampled by gill net.

Water samples were taken on August 8, 2006. Physical and chemical parameters measured were within the range observed since 1983. Seven temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken between June 28 and August 5, 2006. Dissolved oxygen stratification was evident at various depths on June 28, July 24, and July 27. No evidence of thermal stratification was found in 2006. Thermal and dissolved oxygen stratification may result during periods of high air temperatures and low wind. When wind speeds increase to moderate levels (15 mph) the entire water column appears to mix.

This is the third consecutive year that a fall special assessment was conducted on Lake Winnibigoshish. These assessments were conducted with the ultimate goal of converting standard gill net assessments from the traditional summer period to a fall time frame. Fall assessments are conducted on all large lakes except Lake Winnibigoshish. Those fall assessments have proven more effective in the development of, and use of tools that evaluate fish populations in the large lakes. It is necessary to conduct paired assessments (summer and fall) for several years so that comparisons can be made between the two sampling periods. This will allow the ultimate conversion of summer assessments completed from 1983 to 2006 to their fall equivalent, and allow more sophisticated analysis of Lake Winnibigoshish fish populations.

Gill net catch rates varied between summer and fall assessments in 2009. Walleye catch rates were 4.9 per net during summer and 15.2 per net in the fall. Yellow perch catch rates were 52.9 per net during summer and 32.7 per net in the fall. Northern pike catch rates were 10.0 per net during summer and 3.3 per net in the fall. Cisco catch rates were 10.5 per net during summer and 33.0 per net in the fall.

Abundance indices for the walleye, northern pike, yellow perch, and cisco were within the normal range observed since 1983. Walleye abundance as measured by gill net catch rates decreased in 2001. However, the Lake Winnibigoshish walleye population appears healthy with two strong (1994, 1995), three average (1996, 1998, 1999), and two weak (1997, 2000), year classes. One reason for the decline in gill net catch rate may be the low abundance of age one (2000 year class) walleye. Age one walleye are typically captured at a rate of 0.5 to 1.0 per gill net. Only two individuals of the 2000 year class were captured in 2001 which represents 0.08 per gill net. Also, the strong 1994 and 1995 year classes are of high abundance, however, they are reaching sizes that the experimental gill net is less effective at catching. This may result in lower gill net catch rates.

The 17 inch to 26 inch protected slot regulation implemented in 2000 may be contributing to increased abundance of larger walleye. The proportion of walleye longer than 17 inches sampled by gill net increased from 29% in 1999 to 45% in 2001. An estimated 24,000, and 49,000 walleye were released due to the regulation in 2000 and 2001, respectively. However, the strong 1994 and 1995 year classes would likely have caused increased abundance of large walleye without the regulation. Further data collection and analysis is required to determine any relationship between the regulation, year-class strength and changing abundance of large walleye in Lake Winnibigoshish. The mean length and weight of walleye sampled in 2001 increased to 16.6 inches and 1.7 pounds.

Yellow perch abundance was similar to the mean catch rate observed since 1983. Perch captured ranged from 4.8 to 11.7 inches with a mean length of 7.8 inches and mean weight of 0.25 pounds. The proportion of perch longer than 9 inches of 20.1% in 2001 was similar to 20.2% observed in 2000 (historic range = 5.5 to 52.4, Mean = 23.9). Yellow perch captured in mid-lake gill net sets had a mean length and weight of 8.1 inches and 0.29 pounds respectively. The proportion of perch longer than 9 inches of 27% for mid-lake sets was also higher than the 24 historic sets.

Northern pike abundance as measured by gill net catch of 8.0 per net in 2001 was similar to 8.2 per net observed in 2000. Mean length and weight values for northern pike decreased for the second consecutive year to 22.2 inches and 2.5 pounds, respectively in 2001. The observed decrease in mean length and weight was driven by increasing abundance of young individuals. Environmental conditions were ideal for northern pike reproduction and recruitment during the springs of 1998 and 1999, which resulted in increased abundance of small pike.

Stomach contents were examined for all gill net captured northern pike for the eighth consecutive year. Over those eight years the population of prey species has varied by year. During this time frame, cisco and yellow perch have been the most important components in the northern pike diet. Cisco have been the most common species northern pike consume. However, the contribution of cisco in northern pike stomachs was secondary to yellow perch in 2001. Reasons for this change are unknown.

Catch rates for cisco increased to near average levels in 2001. However, the gill net catch of 27 per net remains somewhat less than the historic mean of 31.1 observed since 1983. Cisco abundance indices have varied from 13.2 to 71.1 per lift since 1983. The mean length and weight of gill net captured cisco was 9.1 inches and 0.3 pounds, in 2001.

Assessment of Lake Winnibigoshish is completed annually to track changes in abundance and growth of fish species, and physical and chemical characteristics of the lake. The assessment season typically starts with seining and gill netting in late June to early July. The goal of seining is to sample young game and non game species (including minnows) and to track growth of age 0 walleye and yellow perch (perch). Gill netting is conducted from late June through July to sample game and non game species age 1 and older. Abundance, growth rates, maturity, presence of parasites etc. is determined from this data. Trawling is conducted in August to continue tracking growth rates of age 0 walleye and perch. Trawling gives us the first clue to abundance of age 0 walleye and perch for that year. Temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles are taken from June through August and water chemistry analysis is done in August to track changes in the system that may affect the ability of some species to prosper or exist in the lake. Gill net sampling was modified in 2011 due to a state government shutdown during the first three weeks of July. The shutdown also resulted in no seining, no water quality measurements, and reduced temperature and dissolved oxygen testing. The change in schedule may affect catch rates and may complicate comparison of 2011 data with other years.

Walleye
Gill nets
Walleye were sampled at a rate of 7 per net, which was the third highest for Lake Winnibigoshish. Walleye sampled varied from 8.0 to 26.0 inches with a mean length of 16.0 inches and mean weight of 1.5 pounds. The walleye population appeared to be healthy with all age classes sampled between age 1 and 14. Year class strength was computed for walleye between age 2 and 8. Three average year classes (2004, 2005, and 2009), two strong year classes (2006 and 2007), and one weak year class (2008) were sampled. The last weak year class for Lake Winnibigoshish was in 2000. Mean back calculated growth was similar to the Lake Winnibigoshish and statewide average for all ages, attaining 17.5 inches after five growing seasons.

Trawl
The mean trawl catch rate of 42.5 per hour was lower than average, however, low catch rates may not result in low abundance of that year class. The trawl catch rate of 20.5 young of the year walleye in 2005 resulted in an above average year class. An important factor in year-class strength is growth of those fish during their first year. Young of the year walleye growth was above average through the first week of August in 2011, reaching a mean length of 4.5 inches. Fast growth of age 0 walleye usually results in a strong year class.

Yellow perch
Gill nets
Yellow perch (perch) are an important species for both anglers and as a prey item for predators. The catch of perch in assessment nets reached an all-time low in 2005 largely due to poor year classes in 2000 and 2002. A strong 2003 year class moved through the system resulting in higher assessment catch rates in 2007. Gill net catch rates have been declining since then.

Perch were captured at a rate of 43.6 per net in 2011, which was a new historic low for Lake Winnibigoshish. Perch sampled varied from 5.1 to 11.7 inches with a mean length of 7.4 inches and mean weight of 0.2 pounds. Age classes 2 through 8 and 10 were sampled by gill net. An index of year class strength was computed for ages 3 through 7. The 2004, 2005 and 2007 year classes were average, and the 2006 and 2008 year classes were weak. The previously strong 2003 year class was not well represented in the catch. The catch of perch in 2011 was primarily represented by younger individuals with 95% of the catch made up of age 3 through age 5 fish. Growth was relatively slow through age 2, then increased to average from age 3 to age 9. Perch grew to an average length of 9 inches at age 6.

Relative health of the perch population can be described by the percent of perch longer than nine inches in the gill net catch. The catch of large perch declined to 6% in the early 1990's driven by high angler harvest. Changes in lake Winnibigoshish and other lakes prompted a statewide change in the perch bag limit to 20 daily and 40 in possession in 2001. Several strong year classes were produced during the same time period and the assessment catch of perch longer than nine inches increased to 30% in 2004. In 2005, the proportion of large perch sampled in near-shore gill nets declined for the first time since 1998. The proportion of perch longer than nine inches was about 17% in 2005 and 2006, then declined to 9.8% in 2007 as young perch were recruited to the fishery. Although many small fish remain in the population, size structure has slowly improved. Nearly 14 % of the perch sampled in 2011 were longer than nine inches.

The microsporidian parasite heterosporis has been documented in Lake Winnibigoshish yellow perch. No evidence of heterosporis was observed in 2011.

Trawl
The catch rate for age 0 perch of 10,720 per hour of trawling was average. Growth of age 0 perch was slower than average with a mean length of 1.7 inches in mid August. No correlation is evident between trawl catch rates or growth of age 0 perch and year class strength.

Northern pike
Catch rates of northern pike increased from 1999 through 2005 and exceeded the third quartile in five years between 2001 and 2009. The northern pike catch rate decreased to 7.3 per gill net in 2010 from 10.0 in 2009 then rose to 8.5 in 2011. Pike sampled in 2011 varied from 12.7 to 35.4 inches with a mean length of 21.7 inches. All age classes from 1 to 8 were sampled by gill net. The 2008 and 2009 year classes were most abundant and contributed 61% of the catch. Growth rates were similar to the statewide mean through all ages.

Size structure of the pike population has improved for the last two years. That trend has now extended to the largest fish in the system. More pike longer that 30 inches were sampled than in any assessment since 2000. Increased size structure can be attributed to several causes. Cisco abundance has increased (cisco are preferred prey that provides more energy than other similar size prey), which may lead to faster growth rates. Reduced abundance is also beneficial to the pike population since increased pike density can cause more competition for food and space which may lead to decrease growth.

Cisco
Cisco are a primary prey for muskellunge, pike and walleye. Growth rates of these species can be reduced if cisco are not present in the system. The gill net catch of 16.4 cisco per net in 2011 decreased from the catch of 21.7 per net in 2010 but indicates a healthy population. Cisco catch rates were lower than average for 5 of the last 10 years. This is likely due to warmer than average summer and fall water temperatures that may affect reproduction and cause occasional summer kills. Cisco sampled in 2011 varied from 7.1 to 17.1 inches with a mean length of 10.5 inches.

Water Quality
Two temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken on June 28 and July 21, 2011. Dissolved oxygen stratification was evident only on July 21. No evidence of thermal stratification was found in 2011. Thermal and dissolved oxygen stratification may result during periods of high air temperatures and low wind. When wind speeds increase to moderate levels (15 mph) the entire water column appears to mix.

Invasive Aquatic Species
Species that have been introduced through human activities to a location where they don't naturally occur are termed "invasive". Some invasive species are not necessarily harmful, but others cause ecological or economic problems. Several invasive species have been introduced to Lake Winnibigoshish. Three species of snail: banded mystery, Chinese mystery, and faucet have become established since 2000. Both species of mystery snail appear to have no negative effect at this time. The faucet snail carries a trematode parasite that can kill several species of ducks if ingested. Thousands of ducks were killed by these parasites during the falls of 2007 and 2008. Emerald shiners (often used as bait) are not native and were first sampled in 2005. Each of these invasive species were likely introduced through human activities.

Lake Winnibigoshish is sampled annually to track changes in abundance and growth of fish species, and physical and chemical characteristics of the lake. The assessment season typically starts with seining and gill netting in late June to early July. The goal of seining is to sample young game and non-game species (including minnows) and to track growth of age 0 Walleye and Yellow Perch (perch). Gill netting is conducted from late June through July to sample game and non-game species age 1 and older. Abundance, growth rates, maturity, presence of parasites etc. is determined from these data. Trawling is conducted in August to continue tracking growth rates of age 0 Walleye and perch. Trawling gives the first clue to abundance of age 0 Walleye and perch for that year. Temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles are typically taken from June through August, and water chemistry analysis is completed in August to track changes in the system that may affect the ability of some species to prosper or exist in the lake. Plankton sampling was included in standard sampling beginning in 2012, and was continued through 2015. Six samples were taken on seven dates for a total of 42 samples in 2015. These samples were collected to determine baseline planktonic species composition and biomass.

Walleye; Walleye were sampled at a rate of 4.8 per net. Walleye sampled varied from 8.0 to 26.5 inches with a mean length of 17.0 inches and mean weight of 1.8 pounds. The Walleye population appeared to be healthy with most age-classes sampled between age 1 and 13. Walleye year-class strength was computed for fish from age 1 to 7. One average year class (2011), three strong year classes (2009, 2010, and 2013), and two weak year classes (2008, and 2012) were sampled. The 2012 year class of Walleye continues to be as weak as any year class observed since the start of the large lake program (1983). Poor Walleye year classes occur occasionally. Historic early ice out (March 30 - 2012) followed by a cold spring likely affected reproduction, and growth and survival of the 2012 year class.

Growth of Walleye was similar to the Lake Winnibigoshish and statewide average for all ages, attaining 17.7 inches after five growing seasons. The 17 to 26 inch protected slot limit was in place between 2000 and 2014. During this time, age and length at maturity increased from a low of 14.6 inches and 3.2 years, to 18.0 inches and 4.7 years. Spawning stock biomass increased from 0.5 lbs. per acre in 2002 to 2.7 lbs. per acre in 2013. This indicated that the Walleye population is likely fully recovered from a period of high harvest and reduced recruitment between the mid 1980's and mid 1990's. Due to this, the protected slot limit was changed to 18 to 23 inches in 2015 so that anglers could utilize the harvestable surplus.

The mean trawl catch rate of 2.5 Walleye per hour in 2015 declined by 45% from catch rates observed in 2013, and 2014. Catch rates from 2013 through 2015 were the lowest observed since 1983. Increased water clarity was observed during this time period, which appears to affect trawl catch rates. Fish of many species were observed avoiding the boat during trawling. Due to this (and to collect samples for the "Walleye Fry Stocking in Egg-Take Lakes" project) night electrofishing was conducted from late-August to mid- September. Electrofishing catch rates for 2013 through 2015 indicated higher abundance than trawl catch rates would indicate. Electrofishing catch rates in 2013 (88 per hour) were substantiated by higher than average catch of yearling Walleye in 2014 summer gill nets. Walleye may either avoid the trawl during years with high water clarity, or they utilize habitat that is not sampled by trawling.

Night electrofishing has been conducted primarily to collect young-of-the-year Walleye to augment sample size requirements for the "Walleye Fry Stocking in Egg-Take Lakes" project. Due to changes in water clarity and corresponding decreased trawl catch rates, electrofishing is being considered as an alternative sampling method to collect young Walleye. Electrofishing results from 2014 and 2015 are being used to standardize sampling locations and timing. The following results are from non-standard sampling and may not be comparable with future sampling events.
Results of electrofishing in 2015 were counter to those of trawling. Young of the year Walleye were sampled at a rate of 33 to 201 per hour (data available in the Grand Rapids Area Fisheries Office), and growth was good, reaching 6.6 inches on September 24th. Fast growth of age 0 Walleye often results in a strong year class.

Perch; Perch are an important species to anglers and as a prey item for predators. The catch of perch in assessment nets reached a historic low (at the time) in 2005, largely due to poor year-classes in 2000 and 2002. A strong 2003 year-class moved through the system resulting in higher catch rates through 2007. Catch rates declined from 2007 through 2011 to a new historic low catch of 43.6 per net. The catch rate for perch increased to 57.5 per net in 2012 and increased again to 74.4 in 2013. The gill net catch rate for perch declined to 53.9 per net in 2014. The gill net catch of perch declined to a new historic low of 43.1 fish per net in 2015.
Perch sampled in 2015 varied from 3.2 to 11.7 inches with a mean length of 6.9 inches and mean weight of 0.2 pounds. Age-classes 2 through 8 were sampled by gill nets. An index of year-class strength was computed for all year-classes sampled from 2008 through 2012. The 2011 year-class was weak while the 2008, 2009, 2010, and 2012 year-classes were average. Natural mortality of perch increases at age 8 and few individuals live past age 10. The catch of perch in 2015 was primarily represented by younger individuals with 85% of the catch made up of age 2 through age 4 fish. Although the perch population was composed primarily of small individuals, growth has not changed. Growth was relatively slow through age 2, then increased to average from age 3 to age 8. Perch grew to an average length of 9.3 inches at age 6.

Relative health of the perch population can be described by the percent of perch longer than 9 inches in the gill net catch. The gill net catch of large perch (longer than 9 inches) declined to 5.5% in the early 1990's driven by high angler harvest. Changes in Lake Winnibigoshish and other lakes prompted a statewide change in the perch bag limit to 20 daily and 40 in possession in 2001. Several strong year classes were produced during the same time period and the gill net catch of large perch increased to 30% in 2004. In 2005, the proportion of large perch sampled in near-shore gill nets declined for the first time since 1998. The proportion of large perch was about 17% in 2005 and 2006, then declined to 9.8% in 2007 as young perch from the 2003 year class were recruited to the fishery. No strong year classes were produced between 2004 and 2009. As a result the percent of large perch fluctuated between 10% and 13% between 2007 and 2012. A strong year class of perch was produced in 2010 (reduced to average by 2015). This resulted in increased gill net catch rates (mostly young fish) and a reduced catch of large perch (7.7%) in 2013. The catch of perch continued to be dominated by small young fish in 2014 and 2015. The perch catch of 7.8% longer than 9 inches in 2015 increased slightly from 6.8% in 2014.
The trawl catch rate for age 0 perch of 2,991 per hour was lower than any seen since 2005, and was the third lowest since 1987. Growth of age 0 perch was average with a mean length of 2.0 inches in mid-August. Clear water conditions that appear to have affected trawl catch rates of young of the year Walleye may have affected catch rates of young of the year perch also. Few age 0 perch were sampled in trawl hauls less than 10 feet of water. Catch rates of age 0 perch are typically highest in less than 8 feet. No correlation is evident between trawl catch rates or growth of age 0 perch and year-class strength.

The microsporidian parasite heterosporis has been documented in Lake Winnibigoshish perch. No evidence of heterosporis was observed in perch during the 2015 population assessment, although anglers report the presence of heterosporis in a few perch each year.

Northern Pike; Catch rates of Northern Pike (pike) showed an increasing trend from 1994 through 2005 and exceeded the third quartile (9.6 per net) in four years between 2002 and 2009. The pike catch rate was relatively stable and considered average between 2006 and 2011. Gill net catch rates increased dramatically between 2011 and 2014, reaching a new historic high of 14.1 per net in 2013. Catch rates continue to be above average in 2015 at 10.4 pike per gill net. Pike sampled in 2015 varied from 15.8 to 35.4 inches with a mean length of 21.3 inches. Mean length of pike has been declining as catch rates have increased. Mean pike length of 21.3 inches in 2015 increased from 2014 but was well below average. Age-classes from 1 through 5 and 7 were sampled by gill net. Growth rates were similar to the statewide mean through all ages.

Size structure of the pike population improved between 2010 and 2012. That trend was reversed in 2013 as a strong component of small young pike were recruited to the gill net catch. Two pike longer than 30 inches were sampled in the 2013 and 2014 assessment vs 10 in the 2011 and 9 in the 2012 assessments. Three pike longer than 30 inches were sampled in the 2015 assessment. Decreased size structure may be attributed to several causes. Reproduction and recruitment was strong for the 2011, 2012, and 2013 year classes which made up 94% of the catch, and Cisco abundance decreased due to summer kill in 2012 (Cisco are preferred prey that provides more energy than other similar size prey). A strong prey base of Cisco may lead to faster pike growth rates. High angler harvest of pike may result in a recruitment response (increased reproduction to replace individuals removed from the system). Larger numbers of small pike vs smaller numbers of medium to large pike may cause reduced growth rates due to increased competition for food and space. The recent increase in catch rate may result in slower pike growth in the future. Anglers can help maintain the pike size structure by releasing most pike longer than 22 inches.

Cisco; Cisco are a primary prey species for Muskellunge, pike and Walleye. Growth rates of these species may be reduced if Cisco are not present in the system. The gill net catch of 4.1 per net in 2015 was the lowest since 1983. Cisco sampled varied from 7.8 to 15.1 inches with a mean length of 10.0 inches. Cisco catch rates were lower than average for 7 of the last 10 years. This is likely due to warmer than average summer and fall water temperatures that may affect reproduction and cause occasional summer kills. Water temperatures were warm during the summer of 2012 and caused a summer kill of Cisco. Due to the low and decreasing catch rates discontinuation of Whitefish and Cisco Sport Gill Netting should be considered.

Water Quality; Five temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken between June 22 and July 23, 2015. Dissolved oxygen stratification was evident on July 10th and July 17th. No evidence of thermal stratification was found in 2015. Thermal and dissolved oxygen stratification may result during periods of high air temperatures and low wind. When wind speeds increase to moderate levels (15 mph) the entire water column appears to mix. Water chemistry measurements have been recorded for most years since 1983. Water clarity as measured by Secchi disc in 2015 was the highest measured since 1983. Secchi disc measurements have varied between 12.5 and 19.0 feet. Total Phosphorous concentration can affect phytoplankton abundance which may affect water clarity. Total Phosphorous has remained within historic norms as water clarity increased over time. Recent increases in water clarity do not appear to be related to changes in Total Phosphorous concentration.

Invasive Aquatic Species; Invasive species are species that are not native to Minnesota and cause economic or environmental harm or harm to human health. Several invasive species have been introduced to Lake Winnibigoshish. Three species of snail: banded mystery, Chinese mystery, and faucet have become established since 2000. Both species of mystery snail appear to have no negative effect at this time. The faucet snail carries a trematode parasite that can kill several species of ducks if ingested. Thousands of ducks were killed by these parasites during the falls of 2007 and 2008. Emerald shiners (often used as bait) are not native to Lake Winnibigoshish and were first sampled in 2005. Juvenile zebra mussel (veliger), have been discovered while sampling plankton since 2012. Shoreline and mid lake areas of rock were investigated for adult zebra mussel in August of 2014 and 2015. No adult Zebra Mussel have been discovered in any assessments. Each of these invasive species were likely introduced through human activities.

Lake Winnibigoshish (Winnie) has been sampled annually since 1983. Surveys have primarily included seining, summer gill netting, water quality indices, and trawling. Annual zooplankton sampling was included in standard sampling beginning in 2012, while night electrofishing for juvenile Walleye was started in 2018.

Changing environmental conditions resulting from the introduction of invasive species have caused changes in gamefish habitat and habits. Walleye appear to be using deeper water habitat more frequently, which likely affects near-shore gill net catchability. Methods of data collection have been modified due to these changing conditions. The 2018 assessment year saw standard gill netting changed from summer sampling to fall, and the location and number of nets set was changed to better sample the entire basin. Thirty two gill nets were set in proportion to 3 broad habitat types, which included near-shore, mid-lake, and open-basin (more than 30 feet deep) during the last two weeks of September.

Fall gill nets have been set annually since 2007, along with summer nets. The fall data set is now long enough to be viewed independently, and is likely a better sampling plan than summer nets. Catch rates of fall nets should be less affected by changing fish movements since water depths were sampled in proportion to their availability. Fall netting is also more desirable due to the ability to better determine sexual maturity of fish. Other large lakes are sampled in the fall, and tools that have been developed to evaluate Walleye in those lakes can now be used more effectively on Winnie.
