Zooplankton Sampling was initiated in 2012 and initially sampled 4 stations on Winnie. Station 6 was added in 2013 due to its proximity to 3 resorts and the amount of traffic in that area. Six samples were taken on seven dates for a total of 42 samples in 2018. These samples were collected to continue baseline planktonic species composition and biomass.

Trawling had been a good method to track abundance and growth rates of age-0 Walleye. As water cleared due to the zebra mussel expansion, sampling fish in shallow water became more difficult. Clearing water also allowed filamentous algae to flourish. Abundant algae quickly clogged the trawl and was difficult to clean, potentially reducing the effectiveness of the trawl. Due to this, electrofishing was evaluated as an alternative sampling method for age-0 Walleye. Electrofishing proved successful in replacing trawling, and stations were set in 2018.

Fall assessment catch rates should not be used to compare with Winnie summer data, and be used cautiously when comparing Winnie with other lakes.


Walleye:
The gill net catch of 4.1 Walleye per net in 2018 declined from 5.8 per net in 2017. Gill net catch rates have shown a declining trend since fall netting began in 2007. The apparent trend is likely due to three consecutive strong year classes produced between 2005 and 2007 that affected gill net catch during the first years of fall sampling. Consecutive strong year classes are rarely seen. Average year classes were produced between 2008 and 2013. Reduced recruitment, and resulting low year class strength since 2013 has contributed to lower catch rates in recent years.

Reduced gill net catch in 2018 was also likely due to difficult environmental conditions during the fall assessment. High winds with frequent changes in direction thoroughly mixed the water column and distributed filamentous algae throughout the system. Filamentous Algae coated the nets and increased visibility of those nets to fish. Gill net catches of all species decreased in 2018 indicating that something systematic may have affected catch rates in the 2018 assessment.

Sampled Walleye length varied from 7.2 inches to 23.7 inches, although the majority of sampled fish were longer than 15 inches. All ages of Walleye between 0 and 13 were represented. An index of year class strength was computed for the 2011 through 2016 year classes. The 2010, 2011, and 2015 year classes were average, the 2012, 2014, and 2016 year classes were weak, and the 2013 year class was strong. Recent growth rates have exceeded the long-term lake and statewide averages, likely due to adequate prey densities and lower Walleye densities.

Age and length at maturity are commonly used in Minnesota's large lake monitoring program as indicators regarding the health of Walleye populations. These biological performance indicators (BPI) are typically related to mortality rates of the Walleye population. The importance of BPI's increase when gill net catch rates are thought to be biased, as in the 2018 Winnie assessment. Age and length of maturity for Walleye have changed on Winnie as recruitment and growth rates changed. A 17 to 26 inch protected slot limit was in place between 2000 and 2014. During this time, age and length at maturity increased from a low of 14.6 inches and 3.2 years, to 18.0 inches and 4.7 years. This indicated that the Walleye population was recovering from a period of poor recruitment and relatively high angler induced mortality. By 2008, the Walleye population had fully recovered and began to exceed expectations, indicating that surplus spawning stock was available. Due to this, the slot limit was reduced to 18 to 23 inches in 2015. Age at maturity has remained near optimal, however, length at maturity has continued to increase since that time. Walleye sampled in 2018 matured at a longer length than expected for a balanced Walleye population. This may be due to high prey abundance and reduced competition resulting from reduced recruitment of Walleye.

Spawning stock biomass is another useful indicator of a healthy Walleye population. Spawning stock biomass (pounds of mature females) increased from 0.5 pounds per acre in 2002 to 2.0 pounds per acre in 2008. This also indicated that the Walleye population had likely recovered fully from the period of high harvest and reduced recruitment between the mid-1980s and mid-1990s. Spawning stock biomass continued to increase through 2012, and has been fluctuating near the top of the preferred level of 2.0 pounds per acre since then. Computation of spawning stock is tied to gill net catch. The decrease in spawning stock observed in 2018 is likely due to decreased gill net catch rates influenced by nets fouled with filamentous algae.

Recent low recruitment of Walleye led to an investigation of water level manipulation and its potential impact on Walleye year class strength during the winter of 2017 (Winnie is a reservoir with an outlet dam controlled by the Army Corps of Engineers). Comparison of these two factors revealed a potential limiting factor in recruitment. Investigation of available ice out date and water level data indicates that water levels higher than an elevation of 1,298 and rising at ice out typically resulted in stronger year classes. The DNR has worked with the US Army Corps of Engineers in an effort to create more favorable spawning conditions starting in the spring of 2018.

Reduced recruitment of Walleye has been typical in recent years, but 2018 was not a typical year. Early indicators of a good Walleye year class were observed in shoreline seining. Fall electrofishing was conducted in September, and validated seine sampling with high catch rates. Fall sampled age-0 Walleye varied from 4.8 to 7.3 inches long, with an average length of 6.2 inches during the first week of September. High catch rates may be in part due to water level manipulation and stocking, however, environmental conditions associated with a long winter and delayed ice out may have been the driving force.

Yellow Perch:
Yellow Perch (perch) are an important species to anglers and as a prey item for predators. Perch catch rates have generally declined since 2001, but have remained at or above average when compared to lake class 26 lakes (the largest lakes in Minnesota). Summer gill net catch rates in all assessments prior to 2003 were high, while summer gill net catch rates were generally lower than average since 2003. The perch population will be discussed as it relates to the fall assessment.

Perch catch rates varied from 17.3 to 46.9 per net between 2007 and 2017. The catch rate of 20.2 per net in 2018 was lower than the Winnie average, but above the average compared to similar lakes. Perch varied from 5.1 to 12.2 inches in 2018 with an average length of 7.4 inches and weight of 0.2 pounds. Age classes 2 through 8 were sampled by gill nets in 2018. The catch was primarily represented by younger individuals, with nearly 93% of the catch made up of age 2 through 5 fish. Mortality of perch increased at age 8 and few individuals live past age 10. As is typical for Lake Winnibigoshish perch, growth was relatively slow through age 2, then increased to average from age 3 to age 8. Perch grew to an average length of 9.4 inches at age 6.

An index of year class strength was computed for the 2008 through 2014 year classes. The 2012, and 2013 year classes were strong, the 2014 year class was average, and all other year classes were weak. The proportion of perch longer than 9 inches varied between 8 and 20 percent between 2007 and 2018, with an average of 16 percent. The proportion of perch longer than 9 inches was similar to the long term average of 16%.

Heterosporis is a parasite that causes fish flesh to look cloudy, and has been documented in Winnie perch. No evidence of heterosporis was observed in perch during the 2018 population assessment, although anglers report the presence of heterosporis in a few perch each year.

Northern Pike:
Northern Pike (pike) were sampled at a rate of 4.8 per gill net in 2018, which was a relatively large decline from 6.4 per net in 2017. The reduced catch rate followed an increasing trend since 2010. This decline, combined with reduced catch rates for other species, supports the possibility that gill net catch rates in 2018 don't accurately describe changes to fish populations. Fouling of the nets by filamentous algae may have affected catch rates of all species sampled in gill nets. The increasing trend of pike (as indicated by gill net catch rates up to 2017), coupled with decreasing catch rates of perch, may indicate that pike biomass is higher than optimal. This is further supported by decreases in average length of those pike. Smaller pike need to consume more prey per pound of weight than larger pike. Increased predation due to more small pike can cause reductions in prey species. Perch are a favored prey species of pike. Pike length varied from 15.4 to 33.9 inches with an average length of 22.0 inches. Pike age structure varied similarly to summer assessments with ages one through nine represented. As with most Lake Winnibigoshish assessments, the majority of pike sampled were from the age two, three, and four fish.

New pike regulations were established in 2018. Due to differences in pike biology, the state was divided into three zones, and three different regulations were implemented in those zones. Winnie lies within the North Central zone, where anglers have a 10 fish bag limit with no fish allowed between 22 and 26 inches and only two longer than 26 inches. Spearing regulations vary slightly from angling regulations, and one pike is allowed within the protected slot. This regulation should improve the average length, and number of medium sized pike in Winnie.

Cisco:
The Cisco gill net catch rate remained near the historic low level at 2.1 per gill net. The gill net catch of Cisco has been at or below average since 2013. Low catch rates of Cisco were expected in 2013 due to a summer kill during the summer of 2012. Higher recruitment is typically seen after a summer kill, however, recruitment has not increased since the 2012 summer kill. Cisco length varied from 7.2 to 15.4 inches with an average length of 12.7 inches. The majority of Cisco were longer than 12 inches indicating that the population is mature, and recruitment is low. The continued low catches since 2013 and reduced catches of young small Cisco indicate a population that may be stressed.

Water Quality:
Three temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken between August 7 and September 10, 2018. No evidence of thermal stratification was found in 2018. Dissolved oxygen stratification was evident during August 7 and August 20 sampling. Dissolved oxygen stratification typically occurs during periods of high air temperatures and low wind. When wind speeds increase to moderate levels (15 mph), the entire water column appears to mix.

Water chemistry measurements have been recorded for most years since 1983. Water clarity sampling (Secchi Disk) was accomplished on 10 dates between May 18 and September 10, 2018. Water clarity during May and Early June was lower than observed in recent years. Water clarity is usually high early in the open water period. Reasons for the change in water clarity are unknown, however, it would be logical to assume that the zebra mussel population was reduced which allowed higher density of phytoplankton. Water clarity increased from mid-June through most of July indicating that the zebra mussel population may have recovered.

Total phosphorous concentration can affect phytoplankton abundance, but recent increases in water clarity do not appear to be related to changes in total phosphorous concentration as phosphorous continues to remain within historic norms. Attaining and maintaining 70 degree or higher surface temperatures appears to allow large phytoplankton to attain populations sufficient to decrease water clarity.

Zooplankton:
Zooplankton sampling has been accomplished since 2012 to determine a baseline of zooplankton density. Two zebra mussel veligers, as well as high density of zooplankters were captured during the initial year of sampling. As zebra mussel colonized the lake, zooplankton density decreased, but maintained a relatively high level. Zooplankton density in 2018 was similar to 2017, and density of small cladocerans more than doubled from density observed in 2017.

Invasive Aquatic Species:
Several species have been introduced into Winnie. Three species of snail: Banded Mystery, Chinese Mystery, and Faucet have become established since 2000. Both species of mystery snail appear to have no negative effect at this time. The Faucet Snail carries a trematode parasite that can kill several species of ducks if ingested. Thousands of ducks were killed by these parasites during the falls of 2007 and 2008. The Faucet Snail is a filter feeder and may be responsible for clearing water prior to the introduction of Zebra Mussel.

Juvenile Zebra Mussel (veliger) were discovered while sampling zooplankton during the summer of 2012. No zebra mussel veliger were found while sampling for zooplankton in 2013. Zebra Mussel veliger have been sampled each year since 2013. Near shore areas of hard substrate were inspected for adult Zebra Mussel each year since 2012, and divers inspected likely offshore areas from 2014 to 2016. No adults were discovered until 2016. Adults were found on near shore driftwood in the early summer, then found by divers on mid lake rock structure during August. Zebra mussel appear to have spread to nearly every hard or firm structure by the summer of 2017. Zebra Mussel veliger counts have been increasing, and were higher in 2017 than have been observed in any Minnesota samples to this point. Veliger density decreased in 2018 supporting the theory that the adult zebra mussel population had decreased. Sampling for veliger will continue and the spread of adults will continue to be documented.

Starry Stonewort (an algae) was discovered in Cass Lake during the summer of 2016. This discovery upstream of Winnie prompted an investigation on Winnie. Starry Stonewort was discovered along the south and west shores of the lake in 2016, and appears to have been established for several years. Starry Stonewort continued to spread in 2017 and 2018, and was reported along the east shore of Winnie near Birches public access.

Emerald Shiners (often used as bait) are not native to Winnie, were first sampled in 2005, and have been sampled each year since. Each of these invasive or non-native species were likely introduced through human activities.
Rusty Crayfish are present in Cass Lake, and curly leaf pondweed is present in Dixon Lake. Both of these lakes are connected to and upstream of Winnie. Introduction to Winnie in the near future is likely.

Movement of any type of equipment (boats, boat trailers, boat lifts, docks, personal watercraft, bait containers, etc.) between lakes may transfer invasive species if precautions are not taken. To avoid being an accomplice to the spread of these unwanted species, people should ensure that all equipment is thoroughly cleaned and dried before moving it to a new body of water. More information regarding invasive species is available at www.dnr.state.mn.us/invasives/index.html.

Lake Winnibigoshish is part of the Mississippi River headwaters reservoir system, and is located 15 miles northwest of Deer River, Minnesota. The lake is a large, shallow, wind-swept reservoir with a sandy shoreline and gently sloping shoal areas. Winnibigoshish has a surface area of 58,544 acres, mean depth of 15.1 feet, littoral area of 20,490 acres (35%), and a maximum depth of 66 feet. Water clarity has dramatically increased following the introduction of Zebra Mussels in 2012, yet clarity continues to vary seasonally.

Lake Winnibigoshish has been managed as part of the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources (DNR) large lake program since 1983. Management activities include special fishing regulations, fish stocking, occasional creel surveys, and annual fish surveys. Annual, fall gill netting has been conducted since 2007 using 32 nets. Fall electrofishing has also been conducted annually, since 2018, to evaluate juvenile Walleye production.

A large, annual Walleye spawning operation is conducted at Little Cut Foot Sioux Lake, which is a large connected flowage. The operational plan includes 10% of the egg take put back as fry. The relative contribution from these stockings is difficult to interpret due to the lack of non-stocked years. Walleye harvest has been regulated with a special regulation since 2000. The regulation was modified in 2015 to an 18 to 23 inch protected slot length (PSL) with one over in possession to allow some additional harvest of larger fish.

Winnibigoshish is considered a premier Walleye lake with substantial effort directed towards the management of the species. Fall gill net catches have been variable. Variability in Walleye catches are often associated with fluctuations in recruitment, measured as year-class strength. Year-class strength is a product of natural reproduction and its variability is common on Walleye lakes. Strong recruitment in 2018, and most likely 2019, influenced recent fall catches. A high proportion of the 2021 Walleye catch was age 3 or younger. This suggests favorable angling opportunities for the next few years as these fish grow to a size anglers desire.

Winnibigoshish is known to maintain a quality size distribution of Walleye. However, sporadic recruitment with longer gaps between strong year classes has limited harvest at times. Walleye averaged almost 14 inches in 2021 with fish up to 26 inches sampled, similar to 2020. Walleye within the 18-23 inch protected slot comprised 8% of the sample. The moderate average size observed in recent surveys is a product of above average recruitment combined with a lack of larger/older individuals. The decreased number of larger/older individuals was not unexpected. Multiple consecutive below average year classes limited the number of fish recruiting to larger sizes. Also, reducing the PSL from 17-26 to 18-23 inches in 2015 potentially (by design) allowed increased angler harvest of larger fish previously protected by the more conservative regulation. The proportion of slot length fish was over 70% in 2017 and 2018, indicating few harvestable size fish were available at that time. Conversely, the 2021 survey indicates favorable harvest opportunities now and for the future.

Walleye age analysis identified fish from age 0 to 14 in the sample, and sex and maturity determination indicated a relatively even distribution between males and females, both similar to past surveys. Other population exploitation indicators like female length and age at 50% maturity were within the expected range, similar to past surveys. Half the females were mature at 17.5 inches and 3.1 years in 2021. The female fall spawning stock biomass (SSB) estimate was 0.6 lbs/acre, down from 1.7 lbs./acre in 2020. The decrease in SSB was not unexpected due to many factors. Additionally, it is unclear what the optimal SSB range is for Winnibigoshish due to the nature of estimating the contribution to recruitment and year class strength from the annual put-back fry stocking associated with the Cut Foot Sioux spawning operation. Walleye growth rates have been favorable on Winnibigoshish, typically exceeding statewide averages. Male and female growth rates diverge between ages 3 and 4. Male Walleye averaged 16.5 inches while females averaged 17.2 inches by age 4 in 2021.

Winnibigoshish is a destination Yellow Perch fishery with a history of producing large fish. Perch over 11 inches are regularly sampled. Perch longer than 8.0 inches are considered quality and greater than 50% of this size perch are harvested by summer and winter anglers. The catch for 8.0 inch and longer perch has averaged 8.2/net and the proportion has averaged 34% since 2007. Yellow Perch exceeding 8.0 inches were sampled at a rate of 4.4/net and comprised 53% of the sample in 2021. This suggests that roughly half of perch caught while angling will be of a size anglers prefer to harvest.

Yellow Perch are an important prey species besides being popular with anglers. The 2021 catch was the lowest observed in fall surveys. The catch was near the typical range for lakes with similar habitats, but below average for Winnie. The fall catches have been variable. Inconsistency in fall catches can be attributed to variability in recruitment, angling pressure and sampling conditions. Age analysis identified ages 2 to 8 present. Growth has typically been slower than statewide averages but not slow enough to be concerning. Male and female perch growth rates begin to diverge between age 2 and 3. Length at capture suggest perch begin to reach a harvestable size by age 5. Male perch averaged 7.6 inches while females averaged 8.3 inches by age 5 in 2021.

Northern Pike are another popular species with anglers and are well suited for Winnibigoshish and connected waters. Winnibigoshish tends to have higher pike abundance than comparable lakes, and catches have been relatively stable in fall surveys. Lengths ranged from 14.8 to 30.5 inches with an average of 22.2 inches in 2021. The length distribution was similar to previous fall surveys. It is believed harvest has likely influenced size quality. Winnibigoshish lies within the North Central Pike Zone. Beginning in 2018, lakes within this zone have had a Northern Pike protected slot length regulation from 22 to 26 inches, a bag limit of 10 fish but only two can be longer than 26 inches. Spearing has an exception of one fish in the PSL. Slot sized fish comprised an average of 40% of the sample, since 2018. In 2021, 26% of the catch was within the pike PSL.

Northern Pike age analysis indicated ages 1 to 6 present with relatively consistent recruitment, similar to past surveys. Age, sex and maturity determinations were similar to past surveys, a little over half were female and very few were immature. The proportion of pike older than age 4 was low, comprising 7%. Age-4 pike averaged 25 inches at the time of capture. Anglers and spear fishers are encouraged to take advantage of the expanded harvest opportunities offered by the North Central Zone regulation, but limit their take of fish over 22 inches. Pike growth was favorable, exceeding statewide averages and was similar to past surveys. Male and female growth rates diverge between ages 1 and 2. Age-4 males averaged 22.8 inches while females averaged 25.7 inches, in 2021.

Cisco are an important prey species and an indicator species due to their environmental sensitivity. Catches have been variable, which is often associated with pelagic species like Cisco, but have had a declining trend over the past decade. Warmer water temperatures and Zebra Mussel infestations are two factors that have likely influenced this trend. Cisco lengths ranged from 10.5 to 16.6 inches with an average of 11.7 inches. Length frequency was not very diverse. Age analysis identified ages 2, 3 and 6 present. Age-2 fish comprised 92% of the sample with an average length of 11.2 inches. This year class, as age 1, comprised half the 2020 sample and had an average length of 7.9 inches.

Other species sampled include Burbot, Largemouth Bass, Muskellunge, Rock Bass, Shorthead Redhorse, Silver Redhorse, White Sucker and Yellow Bullhead.

Winnibigoshish has had several exotic or non-native species introduced in the last 20 years. Banded Mystery and Chinese Mystery snails were first noted around 2000, followed by Faucet Snail. A trematode parasite associated with Faucet Snails was responsible for a large diver duck die-off in 2007 and 2008. Lesser die-offs have occurred almost annually since.

Juvenile Zebra Mussels (veligers) were discovered while sampling zooplankton in 2012. Adults were found on driftwood in 2016 and subsequent investigations found adults were present on nearly all firm structure by 2017. Recent zooplankton sampling suggest veliger density has decreased slightly.

Zebra Mussels and Faucet Snails have contributed to ecosystem changes. Both are effective filter feeders and are responsible for a large increase in water clarity. These species shunt nutrients to the benthic portion of the lake resulting in large filamentous algae mats. Decreased nutrient availability within the water column has changed species compositions and densities of phytoplankton, zooplankton and aquatic invertebrates. The impact of Zebra Mussels on the fish community is less apparent and unclear at this time because Winnibigoshish has been fully infested for only five seasons to date. Zebra Mussels have influenced angler use. With the increased water clarity, the traditional mid-day Walleye bite has shifted to more low light periods.

Starry Stonewort was discovered upstream in Cass Lake in 2016. Subsequent sampling found it along the south and west shores of Winnibigoshish, and it appeared to have been established for several years. It was reported along the east shore in 2017, near Birches public access.

Emerald Shiners are not native to Winnibigoshish and were first sampled in 2015. This species is often used as bait and has been sampled while seining since. Rusty Crayfish and curly leaf pondweed are found in upstream connected waters and it is assumed introduction is likely.

Each of these introductions have occurred through human activities. Movement of any type of equipment that can trap or hold contaminated water, plant fragments or aquatic organisms can be a potential vector of spread if precautions are not taken. To avoid being an accomplice to the spread of these unwanted species, people should ensure that all equipment is thoroughly cleaned and dried before moving it to a new body of water. More information is available at https://www.dnr.state.mn.us/invasives/ais/index.html.

Walleye were captured at a rate of 4.3 per near-shore gill net, which was similar to the long-term average for Lake Winnibigoshish. Near shore sampled walleye varied from 7.5 to 25.4 inches with a mean length of 15.6 inches.

The walleye population appeared to be healthy with all age classes sampled between age 1 and 10. Year class strength was computed for walleye between age 2 and 7. Two weak year classes, three average year classes, and the strong 2001year class were present . The 1994 and 1995 year classes exceeded age seven, were relatively abundant, and contributed to the above average catch of 19 to 25 inch walleye. Mean back-calculated growth of near-shore sampled walleye was faster than the Lake Winnibigoshish average for most ages, attaining 16.9 inches after four growing seasons. The mean total weight of walleye per near-shore gill net of 6.0 pounds was also similar to the long-term average.

Cold spring and early summer conditions may have caused lower hatch rates of walleye eggs with slower growth and higher mortality of walleye fry and fingerlings. Indicators of poor reproduction and slow growth were seen in seine and trawl catch rates, and growth of walleye and yellow perch fingerlings.

Yellow perch were sampled at a rate of 73.8 per near-shore gill net. This catch rate increased from the historic low of 56 per net in 2003, however, was still lower than typical for Lake Winnibigoshish. Length of perch sampled in near-shore gill nets varied from 4.9 to 13.1 inches with a mean length of 8.1 inches.

All age classes between age 2 and 9 were sampled by gill net. Year class strength was computed for yellow perch between age 3 and 7. Of these, the 1997 (age 7) through 1999 (age 5) year classes were average, while the 2000 year class was considered weak. The catch of age 8, and 9 perch was much lower than that of ages 3 through 7, and was a relatively small component of the total catch. Relative health of the yellow perch population has been described by the percent of perch larger than 9 inches in the gill net catch. Thirty percent of the near-shore gill net sampled perch were larger than 9 inches. Yellow perch growth was relatively slow through age 2, and increased to near average from age 3 to age 9, attaining a mean length of 9.6 inches at age 6.

Growth of yellow perch sampled in near-shore and mid-lake nets was compared and no significant difference was found, consequently samples were pooled in 2004. Growth was slow for age 1 and 2, and average from age 3 through 10.

Age-0 yellow perch were sampled by seine, however, many perch escaped through the mesh due to their small size, consequently catch rates were low. Trawl catch rates were also low at 6,718 per hour of trawling time. Many young of the year yellow perch escaped through the ? inch mesh of the trawl due to slow growth and resulting small size. Escapement biased catch rates to and unknown extent.

Northern pike were sampled at a rate of 9.6 per near-shore gill net, which was higher then typical when compared to similar lakes, but within the range of catch rates observed on Winnibigoshish since 1983. Pike sampled in near-shore gill nets varied from 8.5 to 35.6 inches with a mean length of 21.2 inches.

All age classes between age 1 and 8 were sampled by gill net. Age 2 and 3 pike were similarly represented in the gill net catch and were the most abundant age classes sampled. Growth of near-shore gill net sampled northern pike was similar to statewide averages, attaining a back calculated mean length of 24.7 inches at age 5.

Gill net catch rates of cisco remained low in 2004. The catch rate of 9.3 per near-shore net was the second lowest observed, and followed the trend of reduced catch rates since 1997. Bony structures were not collected from cisco in 2004 and ages were not determined. Examination of the cisco length frequency indicates that recruitment was sporadic and year classes may be absent.

Lake Winnibigoshish is part of the Mississippi River headwaters reservoir system, and is located 15 miles northwest of Deer River, Minnesota. The lake is a large, shallow, wind-swept reservoir with a sandy shoreline and gently sloping shoal areas. Lake Winnibigoshish has a surface area of 58,544 acres, mean depth of 15.1 feet, littoral area of 20,490 acres (35%), and a maximum depth of 66 feet. Water clarity has generally increased since the 1980s. The increased clarity trend accelerated following Zebra Mussel establishment in 2012, although clarity has varied considerably in recent years. Water clarity sampling (Secchi disk) was accomplished on 7 dates between May 15 and September 23, 2019 and varied from 8.5 feet in late May to 16 feet in late July.

Lake Winnibigoshish has been managed as part of the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources (DNR) large lake program since 1983. Management activities include special fishing regulations, fish stocking, occasional creel surveys, and annual fish surveys to determine the status of the fishery and evaluate management actions. Data collection in 2019 included summer near shore seining, water quality monitoring, and zooplankton surveys during the open water season. A fall gill net survey is conducted annually on Winnibigoshish using 32 gill net sets, and this survey has been the primary assessment tool to determine the status of game fish populations since 2007. Fall electrofishing has also been conducted since 2018 to evaluate Walleye production.

Results
The 2019 fall gill net survey was conducted from September 15th through the 26th. Thirty two nets were set around the lake, sampling all habitat types. High winds and poor weather occurred during the sampling period, which likely influenced fish movement and gill net catchability.

Yellow Perch- Yellow Perch are important as a prey species and are also popular with anglers. The 2019 catch was typical for lakes with similar habitats, but below average for Winnibigoshish. Variations in perch catch rates are expected and may represent variations in year class strength, angling or predation pressure on adult fish, or simply natural variation in annual gill net catches. No clear population trends could be determined. Age analysis identified 8 year classes (ages 1-8). Age 2 and 3 fish were most abundant, making up 31% and 33% of the sample. Growth was similar to past surveys and near the statewide average. Perch averaged 8.3 inches at age 5.

Lake Winnibigoshish has a history of producing large perch, making it a perch angling destination. Perch length ranged from 5.4 to 11.7 inches and averaged 7.2 inches in 2019. The number of perch over 9 inches was below average for Winnibigoshish in 2019, but indicates that some opportunities for catching large perch continue to exist.

Walleye- Walleye are a primary management species on Winnibigoshish, because they are well suited for the lake, are actively managed through stocking and special regulation, and are popular with anglers. The population is maintained by natural reproduction and fry stocking. Walleye eggs are taken each spring at the Cut Foot Sioux egg take site and ten percent of the egg take has been returned to the system as newly hatched fry. The relative contribution of stocked and natural fry is difficult to determine because there are no non-stocked year classes to evaluate. Harvest has been regulated with special regulations since 2000. The original 17-26 inch protected slot limit was modified to an 18-23 inch PSL in 2015 to allow additional harvest of adults.

Walleye were the second most common fish captured in gill nets 2019. The catch was typical for lakes with similar habitats, but below average for Winnibigoshish. Walleye populations are typically maintained by sporadic recruitment (reproduction and survival of young) events that impact population cycles and angler success. Sporadic recruitment is a common trait for Walleye in stocked and natural fisheries, so variations in Winnibigoshish are expected. Recruitment patterns on Winnibigoshish strongly influence the gill net catch. Recruitment was poor between 2014 and 2017, resulting in below average gill net catches. The presence of fish from the 2018 and 2019 year classes was confirmed in the 2019 gill net survey and are expected to contribute to higher catch rates in the near future. Lake Winnibigoshish supports a quality size distribution for Walleye, but harvest regulations used to protect spawning stock can affect angler harvest during periods of reduced recruitment. Poor recruitment between 2014 and 2017 resulted in reduced availability of harvestable fish for anglers. Over 70% of the Walleye sampled in 2017 and 2018 surveys were within the 18-23 inch protected slot. Improved recruitment in 2018 and 2019 resulted in higher catches of fish under 18 inches in the 2019 gill net survey, as 62% of sampled fish were less than 18 inches. These fish were generally too small to interest anglers at the time of sampling, but are expected to grow to an acceptable size in 2020 and provide good harvest opportunities in the near future.

Biological measurements continue to indicate a healthy Walleye population with appropriate harvest levels. In 2019, Walleye lengths ranged from 6.9 to 26.1 inches and averaged 14.5 inches indicating a diverse size structure. Age analysis indicated 15 year classes were present, ranging from age 0 to 14. The 2018 and 2019 year classes were well represented, comprising 14% and 43% of the sample, suggesting good initial survival from these years. The 2013 year class remains the strongest class of adult fish, and comprised 16% of the sample. Growth rates have been above the statewide average in the last three assessments. In 2019, Walleye averaged 14.5 inches by age 3. Evaluation of spawning stock biomass is useful to determine appropriate harvest levels and establish safeguards to maintain an adequate adult population for natural reproduction. A female spawning stock biomass (SSB) of one to two pounds per acre is considered optimal for natural reproduction on Winnibigoshish. Surveys in 2018 and 2019 resulted in estimates of 1.1 pounds per acre. Age and length at maturity are also useful indicators to determine appropriate harvest levels and relative population status. Since 2007, female Walleye on Winnibigoshish typically reached maturity in 3.5 years at 17.3 inches. Both values are near statewide standards and suggest appropriate harvest levels are occurring.

Northern Pike- Northern Pike are considered a primary management species because they are popular with anglers and well suited for the lake. The 2019 catch was typical for lakes with similar habitats and for Winnibigoshish. Pike size structure has typically been moderate, with around 5% of the sampled pike exceeding the angler preferred size of 28 inches. Fish over 30 inches have been present in all fall surveys, indicating that some opportunities to catch large pike exist. Lengths ranged from 10.4 to 32.7 inches in 2019, and averaged 22 inches. Only 3% of the sampled pike exceeded 28 inches. As in past surveys, recruitment was consistent, with ages 0-8 present. Growth was similar to past surveys and near the statewide average, as pike averaged 23.6 inches by age 4.

New pike regulations were established in 2018. Due to differences in pike biology, three different zone regulations were implemented. Winnibigoshish lies within the North Central zone, where anglers have a 10 fish bag limit with no fish allowed between 22 and 26 inches and only two longer than 26 inches. Spearing regulations vary slightly from angling regulations, and one pike is allowed within the protected zone. This regulation is expected to improve the average length and number of medium sized pike. Anglers and spear fishers can help to further improve size quality by only harvesting pike under 22 inches.

Cisco- Cisco are an important prey species and an indicator of environmental change. Cisco catches have declined dramatically on Winnibigoshish, following a trend observed across Minnesota. The cause of the decline is not clearly known, but population trends are likely influenced by sub-optimal climate conditions, interactions with invasive Zebra Mussels, and relatively high predator numbers. The 2019 catch was the lowest observed and is the seventh consecutive survey with a below average catch. The size structure favored large individuals, as length ranged from 11.3 to 17.5 inches. The lack of smaller cisco suggest poor recruitment in recent years. The impact of cisco declines are unknown, but could negatively impact growth rates of large predators such as Northern Pike, Muskellunge, and Walleye.

Exotic Aquatic Species- Several species have been introduced into Winnibigoshish. Three species of snail: Banded Mystery, Chinese Mystery, and Faucet have become established since 2000. Both species of mystery snail appear to have no negative effects at this time. The Faucet Snail carries a trematode parasite that can kill several species of ducks if ingested. Thousands of ducks were killed by these parasites during the falls of 2007 and 2008. The Faucet Snail is a filter feeder and may be responsible for clearing water prior to the introduction of Zebra Mussel.

Juvenile Zebra Mussels (veligers) were discovered while sampling zooplankton during the summer of 2012. Adults were found on near shore driftwood in the early summer of 2016, then found by divers on mid lake rock structure during August. Zebra Mussel appear to have spread to nearly every hard or firm structure by the summer of 2017. Zebra Mussel veliger counts have been increasing, and were higher in 2017 than have been observed in any Minnesota samples to this point.

Starry Stonewort (an algae) was discovered in Cass Lake during the summer of 2016. This discovery upstream of Winnibigoshish prompted an investigation on Winnibigoshish. Starry Stonewort was discovered along the south and west shores of the lake in 2016, and appears to have been established for several years. Starry Stonewort has continued to spread in 2017, and was reported along the east shore of Winnibigoshish near Birches public access.

Emerald Shiners (often used as bait) are not native to Winnibigoshish, were first sampled in 2005, and have been sampled each year since. Each of these invasive or non-native species were likely introduced through human activities.

Rusty Crayfish are present in Cass Lake, and curly leaf pondweed is present in Dixon Lake. Both of these lakes are tributaries to and upstream of Winnibigoshish. Introduction to Winnibigoshish in the near future is likely.

Movement of any type of equipment (boats, boat trailers, boat lifts, docks, personal watercraft, bait containers, etc.) between lakes may transfer invasive species if precautions are not taken. To avoid being an accomplice to the spread of these unwanted species, people should ensure that all equipment is thoroughly cleaned and dried before moving it to a new body of water. More information regarding invasive species is available at https://www.dnr.state.mn.us/invasives/ais/index.html.

This is the second consecutive year that a fall special assessment was conducted on lake Winnibigoshish. These assessments were conducted with the ultimate goal of converting standard gill net assessments from the traditional summer period to a fall time frame. Fall assessments are conducted on all large lakes except Lake Winnibigoshish. Those fall assessments have proven more effective in the development of, and use of tools that evaluate fish populations in the large lakes. It is necessary to conduct paired assessments (summer and fall) for several years so that comparisons can be made between the two sampling periods. This will allow the ultimate conversion of summer assessments completed from 1983 to 2006 to their fall equivalent, and allow more sophisticated analysis of Lake Winnibigoshish fish populations.

Gill net catch rates varied between summer and fall assessments in 2008. Walleye catch rates were 5.0 per net during summer and 11.5 per net in the fall. Yellow perch catch rates were 68.4 per net during summer and 27.6 per net in the fall. Northern pike catch rates were 8.2 per net during summer and 3.1 per net in the fall. Cisco catch rates were 10.5 per net during summer and 11.8 per net in the fall.

This sub survey contains data from 8 mid lake gill net sets that were first set in 1997. These nets were initially set to determine if catch rate and growth statistics for various fish species were similar to those of the 24 near shore gill net sets. After 16 years of sampling it appears that catch rate and size for walleye, northern pike, and perch vary between the two net groups, while growth of fish appears to be similar.

Walleye; Walleye catch rates varied similarly to near shore nets from 1997 to 2005, then appear to move independently from 2006 to 2012. Walleye were sampled at a rate of 5.9 per net in 2013. This catch rate was similar to the catch of 6.8 walleye per near shore gill net. Mid lake sampled walleye varied from 12.1 to 25.9 inches with a mean length of 18.1 inches. As with near-shore gill nets, no age 1 walleye were sampled.

The catch per gill net of Walleye longer than 19 inches has been used as an indicator of quality for the Walleye population. The mean catch of Walleye longer than 19 inches sampled per mid lake net since 1997 was 1.17 per net. This catch rate was similar to the mean catch of 1.18 Walleye longer than 19 inches per near shore gill net set since 1997. The catch rate of Walleye longer than 19 inches was 2.38 per mid lake net in 2013.

Northern pike; Mid lake gill net catches of Northern Pike (pike) are typically less than near shore nets and 2013 was no different. The mid lake catch of 9.3 pike per net was the highest since 1997 but was lower than the catch of 14.1 per near-shore gill net. Pike sampled in 2013 varied from 16.1 to 32.0 inches with a mean length of 21.8 inches.

Yellow perch; Yelow Perch (perch) were sampled at a rate of 72.9 per gill net. This was the highest catch since 2008 and was similar to the catch of 75.6 perch per near shore gill net lift. The mean catch per gill net since 1997 has been higher in mid lake gill nets (82.9) than traditional gill nets (73.3). Although catch rates have been higher in mid lake nets, the catch per gill net lift has varied similarly between near shore and mid lake gill nets. Perch sampled in mid lake nets varied from 4.3 to 11.7 inches with a mean length of 7.4 inches.

Relative health of the perch population has been described by the percent of perch longer than nine inches in the gill net catch. The catch of large perch in near shore gill nets declined to 6% in the early 1990's driven by high angler harvest. Changes in Lake Winnibigoshish and other lakes prompted a statewide change in the perch bag limit to 20 daily and 40 in possession in 2001. Strong year classes were produced in 1994 and 1997 which resulted in high catch rates of large perch in the early 2000's. The mid lake catch of large perch started to decline in 2004 and has declined from 45.9% in 2004 to near 16% in 2010 and 2011, and 14.8 percent in 2012. The catch of perch longer than 9 inches increased to 20.9% in 2013.

Cisco; The Cisco population can vary significantly on an annual basis. Cisco gill net catch rates have varied between 11.3 and 49.3 per lift between 1997 and 2012. The variation appears to be linked to warm summers that cause summer kills and warm fall water temperatures that may cause reduced reproduction and recruitment. The gill net catch rate of 8.6 per net in 2013 was the lowest observed. Length frequency data indicates that young fish are present in the system but age 3 fish (9 to 11 inches) are of low abundance.

Lake Winnibigoshish is sampled annually to track changes in abundance and growth of fish species, and physical and chemical characteristics of the lake. The assessment season typically starts with seining and gill netting in late June to early July. The goal of seining is to sample young game and non-game species (including minnows) and to track growth of age 0 Walleye and Yellow Perch (perch). Gill netting is conducted from late June through July to sample game and non-game species age 1 and older. Abundance, growth rates, maturity, presence of parasites etc. is determined from these data. Trawling is conducted in August to continue tracking growth rates of age 0 Walleye and perch. Trawling gives us the first clue to abundance of age 0 Walleye and perch for that year. Temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles are taken from June through August and water chemistry analysis is completed in August to track changes in the system that may affect the ability of some species to prosper or exist in the lake. Plankton sampling was included in standard sampling beginning in 2012 and was continued through 2014. Six samples were taken on seven dates for a total of 42 samples in 2014. These samples were collected to determine baseline planktonic species composition.

Walleye; Walleye were sampled at a rate of 4.6 per net. Walleye sampled varied from 7.6 to 26.6 inches with an average length of 17.3 inches and average weight of 1.9 pounds. The Walleye population generally appeared to be healthy with most age-classes sampled between age 2 and 13. Walleye year-class strength was computed for fish from age 2 to 7. Two average year-classes (2007, and 2011), two strong year-classes (2009, and 2010), and two weak year-classes (2008, and 2012) were sampled. The 2012 year class of Walleye was as weak as any year class observed since the start of the large lake program (1983). Poor Walleye year classes are expected occasionally. Historic early ice out (April 3 - 2012) with a cold spring following likely affected reproduction and growth of the 2012 year class.

Growth of Walleye was similar to the Lake Winnibigoshish and statewide average for all ages, attaining 17.4 inches after five growing seasons. The 17 to 26 inch protected slot limit has been in place since 2000. During this time, age and length at maturity has increased from a low of 14.6 inches and 3.2 years, to 17.3 inches and 4.2 years. Pounds of mature female Walleye increased from 0.5 lbs. per acre in 2002 to 2.7 lbs. per acre in 2013. This may indicate that the Walleye population fully recovered from a period of high harvest and reduced recruitment between the mid 1980's and mid 1990's.

The average trawl catch rate of 5.5 Walleye per hour in 2014 was the same as in 2013. These catch rates were the lowest observed since 1983. Both 2013 and 2014 saw increased water clarity which may have affected trawl catch rates. Electrofishing was accomplished between late August and mid-September in 2013 and 2014. Electrofishing catch rates for 2013 and 2014 indicated higher abundance than trawl catch rates would indicate. Electrofishing catch rates in 2013 (88 per hour) were substantiated by higher than average catch of yearling Walleye in 2014 summer gill nets. Walleye may either avoid the trawl during years with high water clarity, or they utilize habitat that is not sampled by trawling.

Low catch rates can be explained by extremely clear water during the summer of 2014. Fish of many species were observed avoiding the boat during trawling. Due to this (and to collect samples for the "Walleye Fry Stocking in Egg-Take Lakes" project) night electrofishing was conducted during August. Results of electrofishing were counter to those of trawling. Walleye were sampled at a rate of 60 per hour (data available in the Grand Rapids Area Fisheries Office) and growth was faster than average when compared to historic trawl growth rates. Fast growth of age 0 Walleye often results in a strong year class.

Perch; Perch are an important species to anglers and as a prey item for predators. The catch of perch in assessment nets reached a historic low (at the time) in 2005, largely due to poor year-classes in 2000 and 2002. A strong 2003 year-class moved through the system resulting in higher catch rates through 2007. Catch rates declined from 2007 through 2011 to a new historic low catch of 43.6 per net. The catch rate for perch increased to 57.5 per net in 2012 and increased again to 74.4 in 2013. The gill net catch rate for perch declined to 53.9 per net in 2014.

Sampled perch varied from 5.0 to 11.0 inches with an average length of 7.1 inches and average weight of 0.2 pounds in 2014. Age-classes 2 through 9 were sampled by gill nets. Natural mortality of perch increases at age 8 and few individuals live past age 10. An index of year-class strength was computed for all year-classes sampled from 2007 through 2011. The 2007 year-class was weak while the 2008 and 2009 year-classes were average and the 2010 year-class was strong. The 2011 year class appears weak, however, that year class has not been fully evaluated. The catch of perch in 2014 was primarily represented by younger individuals with 80% of the catch made up of age 2 through age 4 fish. Growth was relatively slow through age 2, then increased to average from age 3 to age 8. Perch grew to an average length of 8.9 inches at age 6.

Relative health of the perch population can be described by the percent of perch longer than 9 inches in the gill net catch. The catch of perch longer than 9 inches (large perch) declined to 5.5% in the early 1990's driven by high angler harvest. Changes in Lake Winnibigoshish and other lakes prompted a statewide change in the perch bag limit to 20 daily and 40 in possession in 2001. Several strong year classes were produced during the same time period and the gill net catch of large perch increased to 30% in 2004. In 2005, the proportion of large perch sampled in near-shore gill nets declined for the first time since 1998. The proportion of large perch was about 17% in 2005 and 2006, then declined to 9.8% in 2007 as young perch were recruited to the fishery. No strong year classes were produced between 2003 and 2009. As a result the percent of large perch fluctuated between 10% and 13% between 2007 and 2012. A strong year class of perch was produced in 2010. This resulted in increased gill net catch rates (mostly young fish) and a reduced catch of large perch (7.7%) in 2013. The catch of perch continued to be dominated by small young fish in 2014. The perch catch of 6.8% longer than 9 inches in 2014 was the third lowest observed since 1983.

The trawl catch rate for age 0 perch of 10,351 per hour of trawling was similar to average catch rates since 1983. Growth of age 0 perch was average with a average length of 2.0 inches in mid-August. Clear water conditions that appear to have affected trawl catch rates of young of the year Walleye may have affected catch rates of young of the year perch also. Few age 0 perch were sampled in trawl hauls less than 10 feet of water during the first week of trawling. Catch rates of age 0 perch are typically highest in less than 8 feet. No correlation is evident between trawl catch rates or growth of age 0 perch and year-class strength.

The microsporidian parasite heterosporis has been documented in Lake Winnibigoshish perch. No evidence of heterosporis was observed in perch during the 2014 population assessment, although anglers report the presence of heterosporis in a few perch each year.

Northern Pike; Catch rates of Northern Pike (pike) showed an increasing trend from 1994 through 2005 and exceeded the third quartile (9.6 per net) in four years between 2002 and 2009. The pike catch rate was relatively stable and generally within the interquartile range between 2006 and 2011. Gill net catch rates increased dramatically between 2011 and 2014, reaching a new historic high of 14.1 per net in 2013. Catch rates decreased to 9.6 per net in 2014. Pike sampled in 2014 varied from 11.4 to 36.2 inches with a average length of 20.7 inches. Average length of pike has been declining as catch rates have increased. Average pike length of 20.7 inches in 2014 was the near the lowest observed since 1983. Age-classes from 1 to 6 were sampled by gill net. Growth rates were similar to the statewide average through all ages.

Size structure of the pike population improved between 2010 and 2012. That trend was reversed in 2013 as a strong component of small young pike were recruited to the gill net catch. Only two pike longer than 30 inches were sampled in the 2013 and 2014 assessment vs 10 in the 2011 and 9 in the 2012 assessments. Decreased size structure may be attributed to several causes. Reproduction and recruitment was strong for the 2011 and 2012 year classes which made up 75% of the catch, and Cisco abundance decreased due to summer kill in 2012 (Cisco are preferred prey that provides more energy than other similar size prey). A strong prey base of Cisco may lead to faster pike growth rates. High angler harvest of pike may result in a recruitment response (increased reproduction to replace individuals removed from the system). Larger numbers of small pike vs smaller numbers of medium to large pike may cause reduced growth rates due to increased competition for food and space. The recent increase in catch rate may result in slower pike growth in the future. Anglers can help maintain the pike size structure by releasing most pike longer than 22 inches.

Cisco; Cisco are a primary prey for Muskellunge, pike and Walleye. Growth rates of these species may be less if Cisco are not present in the system. The gill net catch of 9.3 per net in 2014 was the third lowest since 1983, but increased somewhat from 2013. Cisco sampled varied from 6.5 to 16.3 inches with an average length of 10.8 inches. Cisco catch rates were lower than average for 6 of the last 10 years. This is likely due to warmer than average summer and fall water temperatures that may affect reproduction and cause occasional summer kills. Water temperatures were warm during the summer of 2012 and caused a summer kill of Cisco. Increased catch rate in 2014 may indicate that recovery from the 2012 summer kill has begun.

Water Quality; Seven temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken between June 24 and August 14, 2014. Dissolved oxygen stratification was evident on August 5th and August 14th. No evidence of thermal stratification was found in 2014. Thermal and dissolved oxygen stratification may result during periods of high air temperatures and low wind. When wind speeds increase to moderate levels (15 mph) the entire water column appears to mix. Water chemistry measurements have been recorded for most years since 1983. As in 2013, water clarity as measured by Secchi disc in 2014 was higher than in most years. Secchi disc measurement varied between 10.0 and 12.0 feet. The measurement on August 14 was 11.0 feet, compared to the long term average of 7.0 feet. The Total Phosphorous concentration of 0.022 parts per million (ppm) in 2013 was within the recorded range of 0.015 to 0.051ppm, but was nearly 30 percent lower than the long term average of 0.030ppm.

Invasive Aquatic Species; Species that have been introduced through human activities to a location where they don't naturally occur are termed "invasive". Some invasive species are not necessarily harmful, but others cause ecological or economic problems. Several invasive species have been introduced to Lake Winnibigoshish. Three species of snail: banded mystery, Chinese mystery, and faucet have become established since 2000. Both species of mystery snail appear to have no negative effect at this time. The faucet snail carries a trematode parasite that can kill several species of ducks if ingested. Thousands of ducks were killed by these parasites during the falls of 2007 and 2008. Emerald shiners (often used as bait) are not native and were first sampled in 2005. Juvenile zebra mussel (veliger), were discovered while sampling for plankton in 2012 and 2014. Shoreline and mid lake areas of rock were investigated for adult zebra mussel in August of 2014. No adults have been discovered in any assessments. Each of these invasive species were likely introduced through human activities.

Lake Winnibigoshish, otherwise known as Winnie or Big Winnie, is a large reservoir located immediately north of the community of Bena, Minnesota. Winnie was a natural lake that was impounded in the 1880's with a dam controlled by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers (USACE). Today the USACE maintains water levels within a narrow band of elevation that gives the lake its current surface area of approximately 56,472 acres and a maximum depth of 69 feet. The surrounding geology contains a high proportion of sandy soils, providing an abundance of sandy shoreline with very gradual slopes. With approximately 11 miles of open water between the north and south shores, the lake is prone to high wave action and frequent mixing of the water column when exposed to high winds. During the open water season, this keeps temperatures and oxygen levels much more uniform from the surface to the bottom of the lake, in comparison to smaller, more protected lakes with similar water depth. Some of the major tributaries to Winnibigoshish include the First River flowage through Cut Foot Sioux Lake, the Third River, and the Mississippi River.

Winnibigoshish is often thought of as a premier Walleye and Yellow Perch destination but offers angling opportunities for multiple other species as well. Acknowledging the importance of this fishery, Winnibigoshish was included as one of ten lakes in the Large Lake Monitoring Program, which was developed by the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources in 1983. Surveys are conducted on these lakes annually and typically include a suite of sampling methods that track trends in water quality, zooplankton, juvenile fish, periodic creel surveys, and the current status of game fish targeted by anglers.

Major changes have been occurring within the system over the past 15 years. These changes began around the time of the discovery of invasive Faucet Snails in 2007, followed by the detection of larval Zebra Mussels in 2012, and adult Zebra Mussels in 2016. Filter feeding invasives can dramatically increase water clarity and reduce the abundance of plankton available to fish, including many species found in the lake during their juvenile life stage. Prior to the introduction of these invasives, water clarity (measured with a Secchi disc) averaged 6 to 7 feet and the highest ever recorded was 10 feet. There has been a post-invasion trend of increasing water clarity in Winnibigoshish, which continued during the 2023 field season when Secchi disc readings ranged from 10.5 to a record setting 27 feet.

Walleye is the primary management species in Winnie, and a large proportion of the field work completed is dedicated toward tracking the current status of this species. Walleye catch rates in fall survey nets were up from the previous year, and within the expected range for the lake. The Winnibigoshish Walleye population is supported by both fry stocking and some natural reproduction. In years with the right conditions Walleye year classes tend to boom with one strong year class, which is often followed by multiple weak year classes. The 2019 year class is the most recent strong year class, making up about two-thirds of the total number of Walleye caught in the sample nets this year. These are averaging 16 inches and most reached maturity over the past year. The 2013 year class was also strong, and some of these older fish are still in the system. There is a protected slot of 18 to 23 inches for Walleye, with the intent to protect some of the spawning stock while still providing ample harvest opportunities for anglers. Ten percent of the Walleye caught in the fall survey nets in 2023 were within the protected slot of 18 to 23 inches.

There is a history of heavy angling pressure on Yellow Perch in Winnibigoshish. Perch are also a valuable prey item for predators such as Walleye and Northern Pike. Perch catch rates in fall gill nets have had a declining trend for several years, caused by a lack of recruitment of young fish. Perch reach sizes large enough to be effectively sampled in fall gill nets at a size of five to six inches, which is reached during their third growing season. By 2022 there had been several years in a row with very few Yellow Perch surviving to this age, leading to record low abundance and a population consisting of mostly older fish. Fortunately, in 2023 catch rates did increase due to an increase in young fish from the 2021 year class showing up in the catch. However, catch rates are still below the expected range for the lake. It is difficult to identify one sole cause for the declining trend in abundance with a lake that has undergone such dramatic physical change in recent years. Changes in the zooplankton community due to Zebra Mussels may be leading to lower survival through the first year. There has also been a sharp decline in Tullibee (Cisco) abundance, which would shift more predation pressure toward Yellow Perch. Northern Pike abundance peaked in 2017, followed by the strong 2019 year class of Walleye and both of these predators feed heavily on Yellow Perch. A combination of these and other factors all likely played a role in the decline of Yellow Perch abundance in recent years. While the population has declined in abundance, growth rates appear to be increasing.

Northern Pike is another popular species amongst Winnibigoshish anglers. Tributary inlet areas and connected waters provide a great deal of spawning habitat, which results in consistent recruitment of Northern Pike to the fishery. The population is generally characterized as having high abundance and relatively poor to moderate size structure when compared to other large lakes. Pike tend to have slower growth and poor condition (how heavy a fish is for its length) when population densities are high. In 2023 the fall gill net catch rates were low when compared to historical catches for Winnibigoshish, but still near the top of the expected range for similar lakes. The population peaked in abundance in 2017 and has stabilized at a lower level the past few years. There was a declining trend in condition over the past decade when Northern Pike abundance was high and prey abundance was declining. This trend turned around in 2023 when condition improved to a 10 year high. This is an indicator that prey was abundant in 2023, likely in the form of a good year class of Tullibee Cisco or Yellow Perch. Winnibigoshish is part of the north-central zone for Northern Pike regulations that includes a protected slot of 22 to 26 inches. Release of Northern Pike over 26 inches is encouraged to help improve the overall size structure of the population. About one-fourth of the Northern Pike sampled in 2023 were within the protected slot limit.

Tullibee (Cisco) are an important prey item in lakes where they occur, and at times can be a popular gamefish for anglers. The population in Winnibigoshish has fluctuated over time, but over the past 15 years there has been a steady decline in abundance. Similar to Yellow Perch, the Tullibee catch rates rebounded slightly in 2023 but remain below the expected range. The increase in catch was largely due to the recruitment of young fish that had been lacking in recent years. The 2021 year class made up about one-third of the sample and averaged 8 inches. The decline in the population is likely a combination of several factors. Tullibee feed primarily on zooplankton, which has decreased due to the presence of Zebra Mussels. Tullibee also require cold water and in some years the water temperatures in Winnibigoshish can surpass stressful or even lethal thresholds.

Muskellunge are another gamefish in Winnibigoshish. Available sampling methods are not sufficiently effective to complete population estimates, but it is generally believed to be a low density population that is supported entirely by natural reproduction. Black Crappie, Bluegill, Largemouth Bass, and Burbot also exist in Winnibigoshish, but according to creel surveys the hours spent targeting these species is low in comparison to Walleye, Yellow Perch, and Northern Pike. A five fish bag limit for sunfish on Winnibigoshish will begin in 2024 to simplify enforcement, as this special regulation currently exists on the connected Cut Foot Sioux and Little Cut Foot Sioux lakes and anglers commonly travel between all three lakes.

Invasive species are not native to Minnesota and cause economic or environmental harm, or harm to human health. They are illegal to introduce into or move between state waters and can impact energy flow, food chains, and fish species assemblages. Current known invasive species in Winnibigoshish include Zebra Mussels, Faucet and Mystery Snails, and Starry Stonewort. Changes in environmental conditions affect fish habitat and behavior, which likely affect fish sampling and angling success. Gill net catches have likely been influenced by these changes, especially since the establishment of Zebra Mussels. Zebra Mussels are an efficient filter feeder that have been shown to impact energy transfer and aquatic food webs. The overall decrease in pounds of fish sampled in gill nets since the establishment of Zebra Mussels suggests that there has been a decrease in overall carrying capacity for fish. Movement of any type of equipment that can trap or hold contaminated water, plant fragments or aquatic organisms can be a potential vector of spread if precautions are not taken. To avoid the spread of these unwanted species, ensure that all equipment is thoroughly cleaned and dried before moving to a new body of water. More information is available at https://www.dnr.state.mn.us/invasives/ais/index.html
